{[%evp 0,12,25,26,11,-10,30,7,21,3,8,18,41,33,41] Welcome back, dear Chess
Players, to the series 1.d4 According to Dreev. After our December work on
Catalan for White Parts 1 and 2, it’s time to explore the rich and flexible
Slav Defense. As someone who has played the Slav as Black throughout my career,
I know its reliability and potential for success, even against strong
opponents. When playing against the Slav as White, it’s crucial to choose
the right approach to neutralize the experience many opponents may have in
this opening.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 $5 {My recommendation is the
4.g3 system. Why? First, it avoids the endless theoretical lines of 4.Nc3,
where you risk investing significant time in study and memorization without
achieving much. For most of my life, I played 4.e3, but today it has become
too theoretical, making it hard to find meaningful ideas for White. This is
why I’ve recently switched to 4.g3. Fortunately, g3 aligns perfectly with
our repertoire, so it felt natural to choose this line and share my knowledge
and experience with you.} Bf5 {Bf5 is Black's most common continuation and the
one that better suits the "Slav spirit". We will study it in Unit 2, but in
detail:} (4... Bg4 {Similar to 4...Bf5 in the spirit, but not in the theory,
because now we will play} 5. Ne5 $1 {We will cover it in Unit 1, but in detail:
} Bh5 {We will study it in Unit 1 "Position 1".} (5... Be6 {We will study it
in Unit 1 "Position 2".}) (5... Bf5 {Black's best continuation, in my opinion.}
6. cxd5 $1 {White's best try.} cxd5 (6... Qxd5 $5 {concrete line, we will
study it in Unit 1 "Position 3".}) 7. Nc3 {This is the main position of the 4..
.Bg4 line, and we will study it in Unit 1 "Position 4 and 5".})) (4... g6 5.
Bg2 dxc4 $5 {Concrete and ambitious system, we will analyze it in Unit 3.} (
5... Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. Qb3 {We have already seen the Symmetrical Gruenfeld in
"1.d4 for White part 2", but you will find here those files as BONUS Material.}
) 6. O-O Bg7 7. a4 {will be the starting position of Unit 3.}) (4... dxc4 5.
Bg2 b5 {Will be discussed in Unit 5.}) (4... e6 5. Bg2 {Will be discussed in
Unit 6 and Unit 7, and there are a lot of transpositions with the Catalan.}) 5.
Nc3 e6 (5... h6 {and other sidelines will be discussed in Unit 2 "Overview".})
6. Nh4 Bg6 {Black's most natural continuation. We will study it in Unit 2
"Position 1".} (6... Bg4 {We will study it in Unit 2 "Position 2".}) (6... Be4
{We will study it in Unit 2 "Position 3".}) (6... dxc4 $5 7. Nxf5 exf5 8. e3 {
We will study it in Unit 2 "Position 4".}) *

