{[%evp 0,19,15,17,17,10,36,35,22,-1,17,17,26,34,34,35,35,35,40,40,35,35]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5 {This is the continuation that best fits the spirit of the Slav.} (4... Bg4 5. Ne5 Bf5 {Black's best.} (5... Bh5 $6 {not good.} 6. cxd5 $1 cxd5 7. Nc3 e6 8. h4 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gf1h3,Yf2f3,Yg3g4] Bh5 is misplaced, we can continue with Bh3-g4 or f3-g4.}) 6. cxd5 {critical continuation.} cxd5 (6... Qxd5 {concrete line.} 7. f3 {[%cal Gb1c3] critical continuation.} (7. Qb3 $5 {safe option.} Qxb3 8. axb3 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ye5c4,Yc4a5] We don't have an advantage, but we can aim for a safe endgame. The Nc4-Na5 idea is worth considering at times.}) 7... Bxb1 {necessary move, otherwise we will continue with Nc3.} 8. Rxb1 Qxa2 $1 {necessary move.} ({Without 8..:Qxa2, our position is just better. For example:} 8... e6 $2 9. a3 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next, with a big positional advantage.}) 9. Bd2 {[%csl Yb1,Gd2][%cal Ge2e4,Yd1b1,Yf1c4] Bd2 is useful; it protects Rb1 and also prepares e4.} Nbd7 {Black's best continuation.} (9... Qd5 $4 {was played in four games, but it's a huge mistake.} 10. e4 Qxd4 11. Qb3 $1 $18) 10. e4 {[%cal Gf1c4] The most intuitive and the strongest move. We are ready to play Bc4.} Nxe5 {only move.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Bc3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gc3e5] My recommendation: we protect e5 and stay ready for an active move, depending on Black’s response.} Nc5 {[%cal Ga2b3] Black's strongest continuation, in my opinion. The idea is to prepare Qb3.} 13. Ra1 Qb3 {Black offers an endgame, and it's better for us to exchange the queens.} 14. Qxb3 $1 {the best decision.} Nxb3 15. Ra3 Nc5 16. b4 $1 {as we will see, we can develop a good initiative also in the endgame.}) 7. Nc3 {White's most useful move, so it makes sense to play it now.} Nc6 {by far Black's best option.} ({the natural} 7... e6 $2 {is a mistake:} 8. Qa4+ {the simplest.} Nbd7 {loses immediately, but we should know the refutation:} 9. e4 $1 Bxe4 10. f3 Bg6 11. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5f6] Bxf6 is our threat.} a6 (11... Be7 12. Bxf6 $1 (12. Bb5 $2 a6 $1 $17) 12... gxf6 13. Nxd7 $18) 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Bb5 $18) 8. f3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Re7e6] we wait for e6, which is impossible because of g4.} Rc8 {the most common continuation and probably the best.} (8... e6 $2 {typical mistake.} 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg6] is very problematic for Black.}) (8... g6 $5 9. Bg2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. g4 Be6 {[%cal Gf6d7] Black is ready to play Nd7.} 12. e3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ge3d4] important move because we protect d4.} Rc8 {This is Black's best and most logical move, and now we can play} (12... Nd7 $6 {is not so good now because of} 13. Nd3 $14 {[%cal Gd3f4] and we have the serious Nf4 idea in mind.}) 13. Nd3 $14 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2e1,Ge1g3] Bd2-Be1-Bg3, maybe h4 in the future. It's a very flexible and playable position.}) 9. Bf4 {is White's most interesting choice, in my opinion.} h5 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6,Rg3g4] The best. Black prevents our g4 ideas and is ready for e6-Be7 normal development.} (9... e6 $146 {dubious because of the typical} 10. g4 Bg6 11. h4 {standard plan for White and over the board it looks like Black is seriously worse.}) (9... Qb6 {the most common continuation, but White has the strong} 10. Rc1 $1 {and it's not easy to play for Black.} Qxd4 $2 {natural, but doesn't work for concrete reasons:} (10... Nxd4 $1 $146 {only good continuation for Black.} 11. e4 $5 {also 11.Qd2!? deserves attention.}) 11. Qxd4 Nxd4 12. e3 Nc6 13. Nxc6 $1 {Black loses the exchange:} bxc6 14. Ba6 $18 {[%csl Rc8]}) 10. e3 {My recommendation is to shift now to a positional-style game.} a6 {This is a necessary prophylactic move for Black before beginning the classical e6-Bd6 development.} (10... e6 $2 {not possible because of} 11. Nxc6 $1) 11. Qb3 $5 {We initiate an operation to gain control of the b1-h7 diagonal:} Na5 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qc2 $146 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf1d3,Rd7f5] we prevent Bf5 and are ready for Bd3. The only drawback is that our queen on c2 is misplaced.}) (4... dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O (6. Na3 {is not great because of} b5 $13 {[%csl Ra3] And the knight can be sometimes misplaced.}) 6... Bg7 7. a4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Yc6c5] The starting position of this Unit. White's main idea is to play Na3-Nxc4, after which we are slightly better.} Ne4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ye4d6] The most important line for Black. The idea is simple: to meet Na3 with Nd6, protecting c4. White has two directions: Qc2 or Nc3.} (7... O-O 8. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] Nxc4 is our idea, and if we manage it, White should be slightly better.} Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4] Black's other idea is to use the b4 square.} (8... Nbd7 $6 {For example, after a passive move, White can just take:} 9. Nxc4 $14) (8... Be6 {A concrete move, with the idea to defend the c4 pawn.} 9. Ng5 $1 {Important move, otherwise we are not in time.} Bd5 {In case of other moves, White can just take on c4 and be happy.} 10. e4 h6 11. exd5 hxg5 {Now d6 doesn't make any sense, because the king is already on g8, so White can just capture:} 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. d5 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga3c4,Gc1g5] The best move. Now we are in a concrete position with 22 games, pawn down for now, but 2 pawns are hanging.}) 9. Nxc4 Be6 {Black usually develops first.} (9... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Ge4d6] Very rare move, played only in 5 correspondence games. Black's idea is to save time on Be6, and sometimes play Nd6, from where the knight is very good.} 10. b3 {We can continue our development.} Nb4 (10... Nd6 $6 {There is no reason to go immediately, better for Black to wait for the knight to be attacked.} 11. Bb2 $14 {Slightly better for White.}) 11. Nfe5 Nd6 {And before Black plays a7-a5 himself, White can go} 12. a5 $14 {[%cal Ra7a5] to stop the consolidation of the b4 square. Normally, it is a slightly better position for White, but the engine is not so optimistic, only +0.25. We have to consider however, that the line is very rare and White still has a very pleasant game.}) 10. b3 {And only now Black can consider jumping on b4, but other options exist.} Bd5 {[%cal Gd5h1] The main move. It was played in the game Van Foreest-Sarana, Olympiad 2024. If it is Black to move, they can play c5 and just be fine, because now they control the important diagonal, that's why White should play} 11. Ba3 $1 {[%cal Rc6c5] With the idea to prevent c5.} Rc8 {Sarana insists, but} 12. Rc1 {Very good and useful move.} c5 $2 {is premature, because of} 13. Ne3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd4c5,Rd5e6,Rf3g5] With big advantage for White.}) 8. Qc2 Nd6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Black is ready for Bf5. So White should not ignore it.} 9. e4 {We play for the strong center.} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4] is the best move for Black.} (9... O-O {looks like a normal move, but it is not so precise.} 10. Na3 {We can also finish development.} Na6 11. Rd1 {Remember, that changing knights is not our intention.} Nb4 12. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge4e5,Ga3c4] Our idea could be either Bd2, or e5 followed by Nxc4. For example:} Nd3 {Now we should play} 13. e5 {to attack d6 and capture on c4.} Nxc1 {is the most logical move.} 14. Raxc1 Nf5 $2 {is bad because after} 15. g4 $1 Nh6 16. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh6] The knight is very misplaced on h6.}) 10. Na3 {Standard plan.} Nb4 {Black jumps in with the knight, trying to save a move on 00.} 11. Qc3 $5 {In this concrete case, this is the most interesting option for White.} (11. Qe2 {If we play in the same way, after} Nd3 {The fact that Rd1 and 00 are not on the board favors Black.} 12. e5 $6 {is not strong now, because of} Nf5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rf5d4] And the d4 pawn is not protected by the rook on d1.}) 11... a5 {Most logical move.} (11... Nd3 {makes no sense now, of course, because the queen is on a better square.} 12. e5 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4] Capture on c4 next, with an advantage.}) 12. e5 {This is a very important position. I analyzed it a lot from the Black side also. But I will show you the most interesting directions for White.} Nd5 $1 {was my idea, it is a rarer move, but in my opinion, stronger than Nf5.} (12... Nf5 $6 {is the most natural move, but I think it is dubious.} 13. g4 {Typical move.} Nh6 14. h3 $14 {[%csl Rh6] The knight on h6 is misplaced.}) 13. Qc2 {is the most interesting move, and now Black's idea is} Bf5 {[%cal Gd6c8] Tempo move, and the knight can go to c8.} 14. Qd1 {is my recommendation.} Nc8 {Black's idea.} 15. Nxc4 {Now Black should definitely play} Ncb6 {Black develops the passive knight, only 1 email game here.} (15... O-O $6 {is too slow.} 16. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Rc8b6] Black is not in time to develop, and the knight is very misplaced.}) 16. Ne3 $5 {is the most interesting idea.} Nxe3 17. fxe3 $14 {We take with the f pawn, and it's a new very interesting position.}) 5. Nc3 $1 {the best move order.} (5. Bg2 {is not interesting because after} e6 6. Nh4 $6 {we don't win the pair of bishops because after} (6. Nc3 h6 $11 {[%cal Gf5h7] Black secures the h7 square for his Bh5.}) 6... Be4 $1 7. f3 $2 Bxb1 $1 8. Rxb1 Bb4+ $17 {[%csl Rh4] Black is better.}) 5... e6 {you will face this move in the 90% of your games.} (5... h6 {This is a serious move, as Black secures the h7 square for the bishop, rendering our typical Nh4 move ineffective. The only drawback of h6 is that it costs an important tempo.} 6. Qb3 $1 {we can go for concrete play.} Qb6 7. cxd5 cxd5 {sad necessity because after} (7... Qxb3 $2 {is a standard positional reaction, but after} 8. axb3 cxd5 (8... Nxd5 {It's better than 8...cxd5, but it admits that Black is in a worse position.} 9. e4 $1 Nxc3 10. exf5 $16) 9. Nb5 $1 $18 {Black is lost.}) 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. e3 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7] we can play a typical long and slightly-better endgame because Black's queenside pawns are bad.}) 6. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Yh4f5,Gf5g6,Gf5e4,Gf5g4,Yd5c4] our idea is to exchange Black's Bf5 and play with the pair of bishops. Now, Black has four important continuations, and they will all be analyzed separately.} Be4 {Black's most common continuation.} (6... dxc4 {this is leads to an independent type of position.} 7. Nxf5 {we must capture Black's bishop.} exf5 8. e3 {[%cal Gf1c4] Our next move will be Bxc4.} Nbd7 {most common continuation.} ({Black shouldn't defend c4 by playing} 8... b5 $2 {because after it, he is not in time to defend his queenside pawns.} 9. Bg2 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc3b5] Black needs to defend b5.} Bb4 10. a4 $16 {Black's queenside is collapsing.}) 9. Bxc4 Nb6 {necessary inclusion for Black.} 10. Bb3 $36 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gf2f3,Ge3e4,Ge1g1] Very often, we will continue with f3-e4.}) (6... Bg6 7. Nxg6 {we immediately capture on d3 with the idea to continue with Qd3-Bg2-00.} hxg6 8. Qd3 $14 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Yd3c4,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] My recommendation. We protect c4 and are ready for Bg2-00 normal development. Simple position with the two bishops.}) (6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 {[%csl Yg4,Yh3][%cal Gg4g5] The most common continuation. Compared to the 6...Bg6 line, here the inclusion of h3-g4 favors us, mainly due to the concrete g4-g5 idea.} 9. g5 $1 {It's better for White to start with g5 before including the capture on g6.} (9. Nxg6 {is also fine, but after} hxg6 10. g5 Ng8 $1 $13 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7,Ge7f5] Black will play Bd6-Ne7-Nf6, and the position is unclear.}) 9... Ne4 {This is undoubtedly Black's best option.} (9... Ng8 $6 {Now, we will play without Nxg6:} 10. Bg2 Ne7 11. O-O Nf5 {standard continuation, and now we can play energetically:} 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. e4 $1 $146 {strong move, after which Black is seriously worse.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 $16) 10. Nxg6 hxg6 $1 {Black shouldn't fear the Nxe4-dxe4 structure.} (10... Nxc3 $2 {a positionally bad decision.} 11. bxc3 hxg6 12. Qb3 $16 {White has a serious positional advantage.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bg2 {Black must be very accurate.}) 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 {Against 6...Be4, we will try to reach an endgame.} Qb6 {Black's standard continuation.} 9. c5 Qxb3 {Black must exchange queens.} ({Black sholdn't retreat the queen:} 9... Qc7 $2 10. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gf4c7]}) 10. axb3 {[%csl Ye4,Gf3,Yg4] In this endgame, the pawn on f3 is useful as it controls the critical e4 and g4 squares. Occasionally, we might consider playing e2-e4 or g3-g4, depending on the specific situation.} Na6 {[%cal Ga6c7,Ga6b4] Black's most common continuation. Na6 gives Black the option of either the concrete Nb4 or the positional Nc7. From c7, the knight controls the key b5 square, making it harder for us to break through with b4-b5.} (10... Nbd7 $2 {bad move:} 11. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5] we are ready for b5, and Black cannot stop it.}) (10... Bc2 $5 {concrete move.} 11. b4 h6 $1 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Gc2h7] Black secures the h7 square for his bishop.} 12. Ng2 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4] We improve our knight, and also prepare Bf4.} ({no need to play} 12. b5 {[%csl Gb8] when Black's knight is still on b8, because after} Be7 13. bxc6 $6 {Black can recapture with the knight} Nxc6 $15 {Remember that usually the b4-b5 idea is strong when Black's knight is already on d7.}) 12... Be7 {for sure this is Black's most normal move.} 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Kd2 Bh7 15. g4 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Re6e5,Ge2e3] We can continue with e3-h4 and the key point is that it's not easy for Black to prepare e6-e5.}) 11. Nxg6 {it's a good moment to capture on g6.} hxg6 12. e3 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c7] simple move.} Nb4 $5 $146 {nobody has tried it, but it might be Black's best continuation.} (12... Nc7 {solid option.} 13. b4 {normal continuation.} a6 14. Be2 $14 {playable endgame.}) 13. Kf2 Nd7 14. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc3d1] we can already consider a move like Nd1, after which Black will have huge problems with the knight on b4.} b6 $1 {only move.} 15. cxb6 Nxb6 16. Ba6 $5 {usually we play for two bishops, but now it's a concrete case and it's more important to stop a7-a5, which would consolidate a lot Black's position.} Nxa6 17. Rxa6 $14 {[%csl Gh2][%cal Gf2g2,Gh1a1,Yc3a2,Ya2c1,Yc1d3] Kg2-Rha1 next, or Na2-Nc1-Nd3.} *

