{[%evp 0,16,24,24,24,15,31,31,21,-3,25,34,30,34,20,20,20,19,32]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 {My recommendation, because it's the most interesting line for White.} ({the natural} 5. Bg2 {doesn't offer much chances in terms of fighting for the advantage.} e6 {Black's position is fine.} 6. O-O ({I have tried to analyze} 6. Qb3 {but after} Qb6 7. Nc3 (7. c5 Qa6 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb7b6] Nbd7-b6 next, and Black is fine.}) 7... Nbd7 $11 {Black is doing well.}) 6... Nbd7 {White has some tries, but Black is fine everywhere in more than one way.}) 5... Bf5 {This is Black's best continuation.} (5... e6 $2 {is not good because of} 6. Nxg4 Nxg4 7. e4 $1 $16 {White's strongest continuation and Black is worse.} (7. Bg2 $14 {is also good. We can just play a position with the two bishops.})) (5... h5 {Murzin has tried it twice. It's a better idea compared to 5...e6, but it's not enough for Black to equalize:} 6. Nxg4 hxg4 7. Bg2 e6 8. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ge1g1,Yd2c4,Ge2e4] We protect c4 and will play 00 on the next moves. Very foten we will consider e2-e4, and we are better just because of the two bishops.}) (5... Bh5 {will be analyzed in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (5... Be6 {will be analyzed in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 6. cxd5 {almost always, cxd5 will be our way.} cxd5 (6... Qxd5 {is a concrete line, and it will be analyzed in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 7. Nc3 {White's most useful move, so it makes sense to play it now.} Nc6 {by far Black's best option.} ({the natural} 7... e6 $2 {is a mistake:} 8. Qa4+ {the simplest.} (8. e4 {also good, but 8.Qa4+ is enough for an advantage.}) 8... Nbd7 {loses immediately, but we should know the refutation:} (8... Nc6 {best for the engine, but} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qxc6+ $16 {I guess that we should be very happy about our extra pawn.}) (8... Nfd7 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 {[%csl Rg6] Black faces a typical proble for the 4...Bg4 line.} f6 {only move.} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e4 $1 dxe4 13. d5 $16 {very big advantage for positional and concrete reasons.}) 9. e4 $1 Bxe4 10. f3 Bg6 11. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5f6] Bxf6 is our threat.} a6 (11... Be7 12. Bxf6 $1 (12. Bb5 $2 a6 $1 $17) 12... gxf6 13. Nxd7 $18) 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Bb5 $18) (7... a6 $2 {too slow} 8. g4 $1 {simple way for the advantage.} Nxg4 (8... Bxg4 9. Nxg4 Nxg4 10. e4 Nf6 11. e5 $16) 9. e4 $1 Nxe5 10. exf5 Nec6 11. Bg2 $16) (7... Nbd7 {allows us to exectue our typical plan} 8. f3 $1 e6 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg6]}) 8. f3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Re7e6] we wait for e6, which is impossible because of g4.} Rc8 {the most common continuation and probably the best. We will analyze it in "Position 5" of this Unit.} (8... e6 $2 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg6] is very problematic for Black.}) (8... Nd7 $6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e4 $14 {no need to analyze it because it's clear that White is doing very well.}) (8... Qb6 $5 {interesting sideline, after which it might be not easy to fight for the advantage without preparation.} 9. e3 {[%cal Gg3g4] g4 is our idea} h5 {Black prevents g4, and now we can use a very deep idea:} 10. Qb3 $1 Qxb3 11. axb3 {looks strange, but it's good for concrete reasons:} Bd7 {only move.} (11... e6 $2 {is not possible because of} 12. Bb5 $18) 12. Nxc6 $1 (12. Nxd7 Kxd7 $11 {no advantage.}) 12... Bxc6 (12... bxc6 13. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5] Na4-Nc5 next.}) 13. b4 $1 e6 14. b5 {[%csl Ra7] we fix Black's pawn on a7.} Bd7 15. Bd2 {[%cal Gf1d3] Bd3 next, and pressure on the 'a' file.}) (8... g6 $5 {will be analyzed in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) *

