{[%evp 0,29,20,15,15,-19,42,42,18,-5,40,32,47,19,28,28,57,27,60,45,45,3,40,37,37,41,33,33,36,-115,-115,-101]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 Bh5 $6 {This is a dubious reaction, despite being played around 100 times, even by some Grandmasters.} 6. cxd5 $1 ({After the standard} 6. Bg2 e6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 $11 {Black is doing fine.}) (6. Nc3 $5 {deserves attention, but 6.cxd5 is strong enough.}) 6... cxd5 {This is Black's standard and most logical continuation.} (6... Qxd5 $2 7. f3 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next, and clearly the move Qxd5 cannot be good for Black.}) (6... Nxd5 {Objectively, this is Black's best continuation, but it shows that the move 5...Bh5 is not so good.} 7. g4 $5 $146 {the simplest way.} (7. Qb3 $5 $146 f6 8. g4 fxe5 9. gxh5 exd4 10. Qxb7 $36 {is another interesting direction, but I prefer 7.g4 because it's much simpler.}) 7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Bg2 $14 {Not a big advantage, but certainly playable. The advantage could easily grow in the future.}) 7. Nc3 e6 (7... Nc6 $2 8. Qa4 $1 {big problems for Black. For example:} Qb6 9. e4 $1 {important move; without it, Black would be fine.} Qxd4 {Bayram-Amonatov. Now, White needs to find} (9... e6 10. Bb5 {White develops a quick and inituitive initiative:} Rc8 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. O-O Bd6 14. Re1 $18 {[%cal Re8g8,Ge5d7] White had a winning advantage in Dubov-Belozerov, 2017. If Black plays 14...00, then 15.Nd7 wins material.}) 10. Qb5 $1 $146 {Black is lost:} Nxe4 (10... Qb6 11. exd5 Qxb5 12. Bxb5 $18) 11. Be3 Qb4 12. Nxc6 $18) (7... Nbd7 $2 8. h4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf1h3,Gg3g4] Bh3-g4 next. White's position is already winning.}) 8. h4 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gf1h3,Gg3g4,Gh4h5] White’s strongest continuation, in my opinion. The plan is to follow with Bh3-g4 or f3-g4, targeting Black’s Bh5.} (8. Bg2 {is too slow:} Nc6 $11) ({White's most common continuation is} 8. Qa4+ {but with precise play Black can limit the damage:} Nbd7 9. e4 a6 $1 {important move.} (9... dxe4 $2 10. Bg5 $1 {too many pins.} a6 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bb5 $18) 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. exd5 Bf3 $1 12. Rg1 exd5 {slightly better for White after} 13. Be2 Bxe2 14. Kxe2 $14 {but Black can survive after Be7-00.}) 8... h6 $1 {very important useful move for Black's Bh5.} (8... Nc6 $6 9. f3 $1 {[%cal Gg3g4] g4 is coming.} Bg6 10. g4 h5 11. Nxg6 fxg6 12. Qd3 $16 {cannot be good for Black.}) 9. Bh3 $1 $146 {much stornger than f3 in this concrete case.} (9. f3 {is not so good now because of} Nfd7 $1 10. Nd3 (10. g4 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bg6 $11) 10... Bg6 $11 {Black is doing very fine.}) 9... Nfd7 $1 {only move for Black, otherwise White just plays g4-Bg6-Nxg6 with a huge positonal advantage.} (9... Nbd7 $4 {seriously worse than 9...Nfd7 because after} 10. g4 Nxe5 11. dxe5 $18 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge5f6] Nf6 is attacked.}) 10. Nd3 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gd3f4] we are ready for Nf4.} ({not} 10. g4 Nxe5 11. gxh5 (11. dxe5 $2 Bg6 $17) 11... Nec6 $13) 10... Bd6 {Black's best. The idea is to capture on f4 in case of Nf4.} (10... Bg6 {looks logical, but Black has concrete problems after} 11. Nf4 Bh7 12. e4 $1 {important move.} dxe4 (12... Bxe4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. d5 $16 {concrete problems for Black.}) 13. O-O $1 (13. d5 $2 {natural, but after} e5 $13 {the position is unclear.}) 13... Nc6 (13... Be7 14. d5 $1 $16) 14. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Bxe6 $18 {White is probably winning, you can check it with the engine.}) 11. Qb3 {my recommendation.} (11. Nf4 Bxf4 12. Bxf4 $14 {we are slightly better, but Black is solid as he can continue with Nc6-Bg6, and he does not face concrete problems.}) 11... Nc6 {computer move.} (11... Qb6 {most logical continuation.} 12. Qxb6 axb6 {only good recapture, but it means that White is better.} (12... Nxb6 $2 {looks logical, but after} 13. Bf4 $1 Be7 14. Bxb8 $1 Rxb8 15. Nf4 $18 {Black is lost.}) 13. Nb5 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7] We can play a long better endgame, without any risk.}) 12. Bf4 $1 Be7 (12... Nxd4 $2 13. Qa4 $18) 13. Nxd5 $1 {important move, and the only way to fight for a big advantage.} Nxd4 $1 (13... exd5 $2 14. Qxb7 $18) 14. Qa4 exd5 15. Qxd4 O-O 16. Qxd5 Nf6 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 18. Bc7 $1 $14 {Black has some, but not full compensation for the missing pawn.} *

