{[%evp 0,21,18,18,17,-11,26,29,32,3,36,39,25,23,39,38,37,31,24,36,40,41,35,27]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 Be6 {This move looks solid, but it's slightly dubious.} 6. cxd5 $1 {we have already seen that very often cxd5 is the most interesting continuation for us.} cxd5 {the best recapture, but then the question is why did Black play Be6 on the previous move?} (6... Nxd5 $6 {No need to discuss the knight's recapture.} 7. e4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next, and White is better.} ({also the natural} 7. Bg2 $16 {is good enough for an advantage.})) (6... Qxd5 $6 {This is not good now, because after} 7. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 is coming, and Black's queen on d5 is misplaced.}) (6... Bxd5 $6 {the recapture with the bishop has some human sense as Black's previous move was Be6, but objectively it's bad:} 7. f3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next, and we will have a good positional advantage.} Be6 {Black's best, according to the engine.} (7... Nbd7 {is Black's most common continuation, but White gets a serious advantage after} 8. Nxd7 $1 Qxd7 9. e4 Be6 10. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3,Rd7,Re6] Black's development doesn't make sense, that's why some strong Grandmasters have tried} Bh3 {with the idea to justify Black's last moves, but after} 11. Bxh3 Qxh3 {Kramnik-Kobalia} 12. Qb3 $1 $146 {Black has serious problems. For example:} Qd7 (12... O-O-O 13. Bf4 $18 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 13. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1] long castle next, and Black's position is much worse.}) 8. Na3 $5 $146 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Re6c4,Ga3c4] This move looks very strange, but it's a prophylactic move against Black's Nbd7-Nd3-Bc4 idea.} (8. Nc3 {is natural, but after} Nbd7 9. Nd3 {normally White wants to keep the knights, and now Black has a strong idea:} Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4d3,Ye7e5] important move because it allows Black to continue with Bxd3 followed by e5.}) 8... g6 (8... Nbd7 9. Nd3 $1 $16 {[%cal Re6c4,Ga3c4] Black doesn't have Bc4.}) 9. e4 Bg7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nd3 $16 {[%csl Ga3] the knight on a3 stays better than on c3 because it prevents the Bc4 idea.}) 7. Nc3 {Nc3 is always useful for us, so it makes sense to play it immediately.} (7. Qb3 {immediately it is not so interesting because Black can play} Nc6 $1 $11 {and the engine shows equality.}) 7... Nc6 {more accurate move order compared to 7...g6.} ({after the natural} 7... g6 $6 8. Qb3 $1 {becomes much stronger than at move 7.} Nc6 (8... Qb6 {this is obviously good for us:} 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. e3 $16 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7] we will play a long endgame with the better structure.}) 9. Qxb7 $1 {now starts a concrete line:} Nxd4 10. e3 Rb8 (10... Nc2+ $2 {without the inclusion of Rb8 this is just bad.} 11. Kd2 Nxa1 12. Bb5+ $18) 11. Qxa7 Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxa1 13. Bb5+ Rxb5 14. Nxb5 {Black has an extra piece, but we have a lot of threats.} Bg7 {Black's most logical and best move.} 15. Nc6 $1 {the engine shows an only way for Black not to lose immediately:} Bg4+ 16. f3 Qd7 17. Qb8+ Qc8 18. fxg4 Qxb8 19. Nxb8 $16 {We have recovered the piece and have a good advantage. The engine shows only +0,90, which means that the game is still not over, but we can be pleased enough with the opening outcome.}) 8. Bg2 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Black's hope is to finish in time the development with Bg7-00.} (8... Qb6 $2 {concrete but bad.} 9. O-O Qxd4 (9... Nxd4 $4 {just loses a piece:} 10. Be3 $18) (9... g6 10. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc3a4,Ya4b6] Na4 next, and it's clear that Qb6 is misplaced.}) 10. Qxd4 Nxd4 11. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gc3b5] we prepare Nb5.} Nc2 (11... Nc6 12. Nb5 $18 {is just lost for Black.}) 12. Nb5 $1 Rc8 {only move.} 13. Rac1 a6 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 $16 {We have a huge lead in development and probably a winning position.}) (8... Nd7 $2 {positionally bad.} 9. Nd3 $16 {[%csl Rd7,Re6][%cal Gd3f4] Nf4 next, and Black's pieces are misplaced.}) 9. Bf4 Bg7 {and at this point we can play for a better structure:} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc3a4] 00-Na4 next. It's a new position, but it's clear that White has at least a pleasant advantage.} *

