{[%evp 0,49,13,25,27,0,31,31,31,8,15,15,24,24,24,16,16,24,35,26,26,27,27,49,49,48,58,57,57,63,58,58,63,63,63,71,69,66,66,68,68,68,68,72,85,68,95,76,97,81,92,83]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 Bf5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 {Strange move positionally, but concrete.} (6... Bxb1 {worse version for Black of 6...Qxd5.} 7. Rxb1 Qxd5 8. Qb3 (8. f3 {transposes in 7.f3 mainline.}) 8... Qxb3 9. axb3 $14 {This is a better version of the 6...Qxd5 7.Qb3 line, as Black didn't have to play Bxb1 in that case.}) 7. f3 {[%cal Gb1c3] White’s most principled move. Our plan is to follow with Nc3, which would render Black’s recent moves meaningless. Thus, Black must play 7...Bxb1 to justify everything.} ({I have also tried} 7. Nf3 {but I don't recommend it. If you are ready to sacrifice the pawn, better to play 7.f3.} Bxb1 8. Rxb1 Qxa2 9. Bd2 $44 {Compensation, but less interesting than 7.f3.}) (7. Qb3 $5 {A safe choice, ideal if you prefer not to sacrifice a pawn as in the 7.f3 line.} Qxb3 8. axb3 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ye5c4,Yc4a5] We don't have an advantage, but we can aim for a safe endgame. The Nc4-Na5 idea is worth considering at times.} Nbd7 9. Nc4 Be4 $1 $146 {computer move. First, Black provokes f3.} (9... e6 {normal move, but probably not the best. It was played in the game Sonis-Basso.} 10. Bg2 $14 {This is definitely slightly better for White.}) (9... Bxb1 10. Rxb1 e6 11. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Rf8b4] Bd2 is useful and it also prevents Bb4+.} c5 12. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Gg2] our Bg2 is very strong.}) 10. f3 Bxb1 11. Rxb1 e6 {[%cal Gf8b4,Yc6c5] Black wants to continue with Bb4+ or c5.} 12. e4 (12. Bd2 c5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rf3] Compared to the 9...Bxb1 line, our Bg2 is less effective here since the pawn is on f3 instead of f2.}) 12... c5 $1 (12... Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 $14 {[%cal Gc4a5] very soon we will play Na5, with a small but pleasant advantage.}) 13. Be3 (13. dxc5 $5 {deserves attention.} Nxc5 14. Na5 b6 15. Nc6 Nxb3 16. Ba6 $44 {if Black plays Nc5 we can continue with Bc4, followed by b4. For sure, we have full compensation.}) 13... cxd4 14. Bxd4 Bb4+ 15. Kf2 Ke7 16. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gh1c1] /= . Rhc1 next. The engine evaluates this as equal, but over the board, White may still have a slight edge. Remember, Black had to find several precise moves, and 7.Qb3 has been played only once.}) 7... Bxb1 {necessary move.} 8. Rxb1 Qxa2 $1 {necessary move.} ({Without 8..:Qxa2, our position is just better. For example:} 8... e6 $2 9. a3 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next, with a big positional advantage.}) 9. Bd2 {[%csl Yb1,Gd2][%cal Ge2e4,Yd1b1] Bd2 is useful; it protects Rb1 and also prepares e4.} (9. Bf4 {[%csl Re1,Rf4] I don’t like the bishop on f4, as Black could have later checks like Bb4+, Qb4+, or Qxb2 followed by Qc3+.}) 9... Nbd7 {Black's best continuation.} (9... Qd5 $4 {was played in four games, but it's a huge mistake.} 10. e4 Qxd4 11. Qb3 $1 $18 {Black is lost, as happened in my game against the Italian FM Loiacono:} Nxe4 12. Qxf7+ Kd8 13. Ba5+ $1 {Dreev-Loiacono, 2019.}) (9... Qe6 $2 {too slow.} 10. e4 {[%cal Gf1c4] Bc4 is a huge threat.} Qc8 {only move. Black’s last moves placed the queen in a safe spot but didn’t aid development, giving us a significant advantage.} 11. Qb3 $1 $146 (11. d5 $6 e6 $1 12. dxe6 Qxe6 13. Bc3 b5 $1 $132 {[%cal Rf1c4] strong move that stops Bc4, and Black was fine in Millkow-Brunello, 2022.}) 11... e6 12. Bh3 {[%csl Gh3] we play for domination.} Be7 13. Rc1 O-O 14. O-O $16 {Black cannot move anything without allowing some tactical ideas. For example, 14...Nbd7 would allow the 15.Nxf7 tactical idea.}) (9... Nfd7 $5 $146 {Nobody has tried this move, but it’s useful to know how to respond. It’s the engine’s second-best line.} 10. Nd3 $1 {[%csl Rb8,Rd7] Black needs to justify his strange knights.} (10. e4 {is not so good as after 9...Nbd7 because after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 {[%csl Gb8,Re5][%cal Re5f6] we don't attack Black's knight on f6, and Black is in time to consolidate:} Qe6 12. Bc3 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7] e6-Be7 next.}) 10... e6 11. e4 {Black's position looks very risky, but the engine finds the fantastic} Qa6 $3 {The only move to prevent White from gaining a big advantage. We’re still pressing after} 12. Be3 (12. b4 $5 {deserves attention.}) 12... Be7 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Qb6 15. b4 $36 {We not only have compensation but also a strong initiative. However, Black is still in the game and can defend with accurate play.}) 10. e4 {[%cal Gf1c4] The most intuitive and the strongest move. We are ready to play Bc4.} ({Black is doing fine after} 10. Nd3 Qd5 11. Bc3 e6 $132 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] followed by normal development like Be7-00.}) 10... Nxe5 {only move.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Bc3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gc3e5] My recommendation: we protect e5 and stay ready for an active move, depending on Black’s response.} (12. f4 {has also been tried, but I don't like it.} e6 $132 {[%csl Rf4] 12.Bc3 is better because the bishop on c3 is much more useful than the pawn on f4.}) 12... Nc5 {[%cal Ga2b3] Black's strongest continuation, in my opinion. The idea is to prepare Qb3.} (12... Nb6 $6 13. Ra1 Qe6 {Millkow-Kramnik, 2023.} 14. f4 $1 {[%cal Gf4f5] f5 is our idea.} Qd7 (14... g6 {looks logical to stop f5, but after} 15. h4 $1 $18 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf1h3,Gh4h5] Black is in huge trouble because we are ready for h5 or Bh3 on the next move.}) 15. Qb3 $1 {we prepare a strong tactical idea.} e6 (15... Qc7 16. e6 $1 $18 {positionally lost for Black.}) 16. Qxb6 $1 axb6 17. Rxa8+ Ke7 18. f5 $1 exf5 19. Bc4 $16 {Black will need engine-like precision to avoid immediate loss, and it’s unclear if the position can even be saved objectively.}) (12... Rd8 13. Ra1 Qe6 14. Qd4 $36 {[%cal Gf1c4,Ya1a7] looks very promising for White because we are ready for Rxa7 or for Bc4.}) 13. Ra1 Qb3 {Black offers an endgame, and it's better for us to exchange the queens.} (13... Qe6 $2 {doesn't make any sense, at least because of} 14. b4 $1 $16) 14. Qxb3 $1 {the best decision.} ({If you decide to keep the queens, for example by playing} 14. Qc1 $6 {after} e6 $36 {Black will finish his development, and I don't see a lot of interesting ideas for us.}) 14... Nxb3 15. Ra3 Nc5 16. b4 $1 {as we will see, we can develop a good initiative also in the endgame.} Ne6 {has been played in the only game that reached the position.} (16... Nd7 $5 $146 {Engine's novelty.} 17. e6 $1 {strong positional sacrifice.} (17. f4 $2 {is not in the spirit, because after} e6 $17 {Black will complete the development and slowly try to use his extra pawn.}) 17... fxe6 18. Bc4 {An interesting position. We can proceed with e5-Bxe6-Ke2, aiming for positional domination.} e5 {the most logical move.} 19. Be6 {Black needs to develop.} g6 20. Ke2 Bg7 21. Rd1 {[%csl Re8] it's not easy to solve the problems with Ke8.} Nf8 {only move.} 22. Bc4 Nd7 {Black can adopt a waiting strategy, as the engine suggests.} 23. Bb2 $5 {[%cal Ga3d3] useful move. Sometimes, Rad3 could be our idea.} a6 {looks normal.} 24. Rad3 Nf8 (24... Nb6 $2 25. Bb3 $18 {[%cal Gb2c1,Gc1e3] Our position is winning. Just Bc1-Be3 next.}) 25. f4 h5 $1 {only move for Black.} 26. fxe5 $36 {The engine shows "0.00", but over the board, I don't know how many players would like to play it from the Black's side.}) 17. b5 $1 Nc7 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. e6 $1 $146 {very strong positional idea. While 19...fxe6 is terrible for obvious positional reasons, after} (19. Bc4 $6 e6 $132 {Black was fine in the game Rodshtein-Gurel, 2024.}) 19... Nxe6 {we can play} 20. Ra6 $44 {[%cal Ga6c6,Gf1b5] we want to take on c6, followed by Bb5. Despite our two pawns deficit, it's still not easy to play for Black. For example:} Nd8 {logical move.} 21. Bc4 e6 22. Ke2 f6 {Black needs to spend another tempo before developing the bishop.} 23. Bd4 Bd6 (23... Be7 {looks safe, but after} 24. f4 $1 O-O 25. h4 $36 {We dominate the board, and it's not easy at all to play form the Black's side. If you don't believe me, try to play this with Black against an engine.}) 24. Rd1 Ke7 25. Rda1 $44 {Very likely it will be a draw, but we still have practical chances. For example, 25...Re8 is Black's only move now.} *

