{[%evp 0,25,18,17,17,-14,31,31,31,3,38,23,25,12,37,37,37,22,45,43,39,39,43,15,15,-9,24,36]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 Bf5 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. f3 g6 $5 {this move is less common than 8...Rc8, but it's also a playable continuation for Black.} 9. Bg2 (9. e4 $5 {It's an interesting concrete move, but if our opponent knows it it becomes less interesting :).} dxe4 $1 {Black has to accept the challenge.} (9... Be6 $2 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5 $16 {positionally better for White.}) 10. Bb5 {and now Black has a lot of good continuations, for example:} Nd7 (10... Bd7 $5 {could be a good and solid alternative.}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6 exf3 $13 {Very complicated position, and the game goes for three results. In addition, Black has also some other options at move 10, and that's why I don't like 9.e4.}) 9... Bg7 10. O-O {This is my recommendation. First of all, we wait for Black's next move.} (10. e4 {also here I don't like e4:} dxe4 11. fxe4 Be6 $132 {I think Black is doing great. For example:} 12. Nxc6 (12. Nf3 Bg4 $1 13. Be3 O-O 14. O-O Ne8 $13 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8d8] Qd7-Rd8 next, and I am not sure about which color should play for equality now.}) 12... bxc6 13. O-O O-O 14. e5 Nd5 15. Na4 {no problem for Black after different moves:} Nb6 $5 $132 (15... f6 16. Nc5 Qc8 $132)) 10... O-O {this natural move has been played in all the games that reached this position.} (10... Rc8 $5 $146 {has never been tried, but it's a serious alternative.} 11. e4 $1 {[%csl Rc8] only in this concrete case I suggest to play e4. The reason is that Black's rook on c8 will be misplaced in the following line:} dxe4 (11... Be6 $2 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. e5 $16 {much better positionally for us.}) 12. fxe4 Be6 {standard reaction for Black, and now} 13. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 14. e5 Nd5 (14... Nd7 {is slightly more precise than Nd5, but after} 15. Bf4 O-O 16. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4] We can continue with Na4 next, and we have a small but pleasant advantage.}) 15. Na4 $14 {[%csl Rc8] Rc8 is misplaced. We will play Nc5 next, with a very pleasant advantage.}) 11. g4 Be6 {[%cal Gf6d7] Black is ready to play Nd7.} (11... Bd7 12. Bg5 $36 {looks interesting for us. The computer plays h5, but it's a new position and I don't think it will be easy to play for Black.}) (11... Bc8 {[%csl Yd7][%cal Gf6d7] was played in an email game.} 12. e3 (12. h3 $5 {could be an interesting alternative, because after} Nd7 13. f4 Ndxe5 $6 ({Black should instead start with} 13... e6 {and after} 14. Be3 f6 15. Nf3 Nb6 16. Bf2 $14 {[%cal Gb2b3,Ga1c1,Ye2e4] we can continue with the useful moves Rc1-b3, and sometimes play e2-e4 in one tempo. We don't have a big advantage, but our position has for sure better perspectives.}) 14. fxe5 e6 {[%csl Gh3] h3 is more useful than 12.e3 and we can continue with} 15. e4 dxe4 16. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4] Nxe4 next.}) 12... Nd7 {that's why Black has retreated the bishop on c8 and not on d7.} 13. f4 Ndxe5 14. fxe5 e6 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black wants to continue with e6, and that's why I suggest an original idea:} 15. g5 $5 $146 {[%cal Rf7f6] we stop f6, and after} Qxg5 16. e4 Qd8 17. Be3 $36 {We have an interesting practical initiative.}) 12. e3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ge3d4] important move because we protect d4.} Rc8 {This is Black's best and most logical move, and now we can play} (12... Nd7 $6 {is not so good now because of} 13. Nd3 $14 {[%cal Gd3f4] and we have the serious Nf4 idea in mind.} (13. f4 $6 {not good because of} Ndxe5 $1 14. fxe5 f6 $1 $11 {and Black is fine.})) (12... Nxe5 $6 13. dxe5 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4] f4 next.}) (12... Ne8 {was tried in the game Davtyan-Subelj.} 13. f4 $1 $16 {is a better move. Compared to 12...Nd7, Black does not have Ndxe5, and is just worse.} (13. Nd3 {was White's choice, and now Black played the strong} Bc8 $1 {[%csl Ge8] which shows the difference between 12...Ne8 and 12...Nd7.} 14. f4 e6 $14 {[%cal Ge8d6] /=. Black has a good d6 square for his knight. Our position is still more pleasant, but is very playable also for Black.})) 13. Nd3 $14 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2e1,Ge1g3] Bd2-Be1-Bg3, maybe h4 in the future. It's a very flexible and playable position.} ({We can see how some games continued from this point:} 13. Nd3 Bd7 $146 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf6e8,Ge8d6] is probably Black's best continuation, with the idea to continue with e6-Ne8-Nd6.} (13... Nd7 $6 14. Nf4 Nb6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. f4 $16 {Wagner-Osmak.}) (13... Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] Black's knight looks on c4, and it was played in the game Arabidze-Onur, and now I recommend} 14. Qe1 $1 $14 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Ge1c3,Gb2b3] We protect our knight on c3 and are ready to play b3, limiting Black's knight on a5.}) 14. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2e1,Ge1g3] we will now improve our bishop.} e6 15. Be1 Ne8 16. Bg3 $14 {Black is solid, but it's definitely slightly better for us.}) *

