{[%evp 0,29,15,20,15,-4,39,37,23,8,15,15,24,24,34,34,34,11,41,38,73,58,32,21,31,31,62,31,38,45,23,23]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 Bf5 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. f3 Rc8 {Black's most common continuation. My recommendation is 9.Bf4, but first, let’s explore why other moves are less effective.} 9. Bf4 {is White's most interesting choice, in my opinion.} (9. e4 $6 {too optimistic.} dxe4 10. Bb5 e6 $1 $17 {Black is better.}) ({I also thought about} 9. e3 {but after} h5 $132 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Rg3g4] Black stops g4 and has an easy game.}) (9. Bg2 {I don't like it.} h6 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge7e6] e6 next, Black's position is fine and he can continue with very natural moves.}) (9. g4 Bd7 $1 10. Bf4 (10. Nxd7 $6 Nxd7 $15 {[%cal Ge7e5,Rd8h4] e5, followed by Qh4+ is a big threat.}) 10... e6 11. e3 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bc6 $132 {[%cal Gh7h5] h5 next, and Black has a comfortable position, which he can also play for three results.}) 9... h5 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6] The best. Black prevents our g4 ideas and is ready for e6-Be7 normal development.} (9... Qb6 {the most common continuation, but White has the strong} 10. Rc1 $1 {and it's not easy to play for Black.} Nxd4 $1 $146 {only good continuation for Black.} (10... Qxd4 $2 {natural, but doesn't work for concrete reasons:} 11. Qxd4 Nxd4 12. e3 Nc6 13. Nxc6 $1 {Black loses the exchange:} bxc6 14. Ba6 $18 {[%csl Rc8]}) (10... e6 11. Na4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb6] White shows that Black's Qb6 is misplaced.}) 11. e4 $5 {also 11.Qd2!? deserves attention.} dxe4 12. fxe4 Nxe4 (12... Bd7 $2 13. Nc4 $1 $16 {Black has to sacrifice the exchange on c4.}) 13. Qa4+ $1 {important.} Rc6 {only move for Black.} 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Be3 e5 16. Bxd4 $1 {important move to remember.} Nxc3 {only move.} (16... exd4 $2 17. Nd5 $18) 17. Rxc3 exd4 18. Rb3 Qc5 $1 19. Qc4 $36 {We might not win this against a computer, but White clearly stands better, and over the board, Black can easily lose quickly.}) (9... e6 $146 {nobody has tried it because it looks very bad, but it's not so bad if Black follows the engine's recommendations.} 10. g4 Bg6 11. h4 {standard plan for White and over the board it looks like Black is seriously worse.} Qb6 $1 {here starts engine's play.} 12. Qb3 $5 {Looks like an interesting positional option to the most principled 12.h5.} (12. h5 {principled continuation.} Qxb2 $1 {Black must go for concrete complications.} 13. hxg6 Qxc3+ 14. Kf2 fxg6 15. Nxg6 Rg8 {the engine approves this for Black and thinks that White is only very slightly better after} 16. Rc1 Qa3 {I will just show you the engine's first line, so that you can understand.} 17. Ne5 g5 $1 18. Bd2 Rc7 $1 19. e3 Bd6 $1 20. Bb5 Kf8 $1 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Qb3 Qxb3 23. axb3 $36 {Risk-free for White, but objectively fine for Black.}) 12... Qxb3 $1 (12... Nxd4 $2 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Rd1 $1 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5] big problems for Black because h5 is still a threat.}) 13. axb3 a6 $1 {only move.} 14. Rc1 {[%cal Gh4h5,Rg6c2] we prevent Bc2 and are ready for h5.} (14. h5 {is not good because of} Bc2 $11) 14... Nxd4 $1 {also here, the engine shows fantastic defensive resources for Black:} 15. h5 Bxh5 $1 16. gxh5 Nxb3 17. Rd1 {I would never think that Black has full compensation, but it looks like this is the case.} d4 $1 18. Ne4 Nd5 19. Nd3 Be7 20. Nd6+ (20. h6 $5 g6 21. Bg3 $132 {deserves attention.}) 20... Bxd6 21. Bxd6 $13 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gd5e3] Black has full compensation after 21...Ne3 or 21...Kd7. However, over the board, it’s not always easy for Black to find the best moves, so I’m comfortable playing this as White.}) (9... Bd7 {solid but passive.} 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. e4 $1 ({if we just play for two bishops, for example} 11. e3 {then after} e6 $132 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gf6h5] Black can always consider Nh5 or Bd6, and we are not better.}) 11... e6 12. e5 Ng8 13. Be3 $14 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1,Ye3d4] Bd3-00 next, and we are for sure slightly better.}) 10. e3 {My recommendation is to shift now to a positional-style game.} (10. e4 {leads to a draw} dxe4 11. Bb5 e6 $1 12. Qa4 Qb6 (12... a6 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 13. Nc4 Qd8 14. Ne5 $11 {I didn't find anything better for White than to repeat the moves.} (14. Qxa7 {too risky.} Bb4 15. Qxb7 O-O $1 16. Bxc6 Qxd4 $13 {too complicated for my taste.})) ({I have also considered} 10. Nxc6 {but Black is not forced to recapture with the pawn:} Rxc6 $1 (10... bxc6 11. e3 $14 {could be interesting for us.}) 11. e4 dxe4 12. Bb5 e6 $44 {Black will have full compensation for the exchange.}) 10... a6 {This is a necessary prophylactic move for Black before beginning the classical e6-Bd6 development.} (10... e6 $2 {not possible because of} 11. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 (11... Rxc6 12. Bb5 $18 {[%csl Rc6]}) 12. Ba6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc8] Black loses a full exchange.}) 11. Qb3 $5 {We initiate an operation to gain control of the b1-h7 diagonal:} Na5 12. Qa4+ Bd7 (12... b5 $2 13. Nxb5 $1 $16 {typical tactic.}) 13. Qc2 $146 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf1d3,Rd7f5] we prevent Bf5 and are ready for Bd3. The only drawback is that our queen on c2 is misplaced.} e6 14. Bd3 Nc6 15. a3 $132 {We’ve reached an Exchange Slav-type position, though slightly atypical due to our pawn on g3 and Black’s pawn on h5. While we don’t have an advantage, this position is certainly playable over the board.} *

