{[%evp 0,12,28,22,27,0,31,16,16,0,-1,-16,17,17,17]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5 {This is the continuation that best fits the spirit of the Slav.} 5. Nc3 $1 {the best move order.} (5. Bg2 {is not interesting because after} e6 6. Nc3 (6. Nh4 $6 {we don't win the pair of bishops because after} Be4 $1 7. f3 $2 Bxb1 $1 8. Rxb1 Bb4+ $17 {Black is better.}) 6... h6 $11 {[%cal Gf5h7] Black secures the h7 square for his Bh5.}) 5... e6 {you will face this move in the 90% of your games.} (5... dxc4 {immediately it is not so good because after} 6. Ne5 {[%csl Gg3] We are playing a well-known variation of the classical Slav (1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 dxc4 5.a4 Bf5 6.Ne5), but here, instead of a4, we have played g3—a detail that clearly works in our favor.} Nbd7 (6... e6 7. Bg2 $16 {[%cal Ge5c4] Nxc4 next.}) 7. Nxc4 b5 {this is probably Black's only interesting try, using the fact that White doesn't have the pawn on a4.} (7... Qc7 $2 {is an important line when White has a4 instead of g3, but here it doesn't make sense because of} 8. Bf4 $16) (7... Nb6 8. Ne5 Nfd7 9. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1] Bg2-00 next, with a very good game for White.}) 8. Ne3 $1 {we win an important tempo on Bf5.} Bg6 9. Bg2 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gg2c6]} Rc8 {and now it's a very important moment.} 10. d5 $1 {important to play it before Black has played e7-e6.} ({after the natural} 10. O-O {Black plays} e6 $11 {and the position is just equal.}) 10... b4 {only critical move.} 11. dxc6 bxc3 12. cxd7+ Qxd7 13. bxc3 $14 {The engine might hold with precise play, but from a human perspective, this position is definitely at least interesting for us.}) (5... a6 {this is a serious line in the 4.e3 Slav, but here it's just a waste of time:} 6. Bg2 e6 7. Nh4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Gg2] I am sure that the inclusion of Bg2 and a6 will work well for us if we compare this position to the 5...e6 6.Nh4 mainline.}) (5... Nbd7 {this is not great at least because after} 6. cxd5 cxd5 {[%csl Rd7] Black's knight on d7 is misplaced in the exchange-Slav structure.} 7. Bg2 e6 8. Nh4 $14 {[%csl Rd7]}) (5... h6 {This is a serious move, as Black secures the h7 square for the bishop, rendering our typical Nh4 move ineffective. The only drawback of h6 is that it costs an important tempo.} 6. Qb3 $1 {we can go for concrete play.} Qb6 7. cxd5 cxd5 {sad necessity because after} (7... Qxb3 $2 {is a standard positional reaction, but after} 8. axb3 cxd5 (8... Nxd5 {It's better than 8...cxd5, but it admits that Black is in a worse position.} 9. e4 $1 Nxc3 10. exf5 $16) 9. Nb5 $1 $18 {Black is lost.}) 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. e3 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7] we can play a typical long and slightly-better endgame because Black's queenside pawns are bad.}) 6. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Yh4f5] our idea is to exchange Black's Bf5 and play with the pair of bishops. Now, Black has four important continuations, and they will all be analyzed separately.} dxc4 {Position 4 of this Unit.} (6... Bg6 {Position 1 of this Unit.}) (6... Bg4 {Position 2 of this Unit.}) (6... Be4 {Position 3 of this Unit.}) *

