{[%evp 0,35,27,22,22,-10,37,10,32,8,10,27,33,37,37,37,37,-2,10,18,32,32,32,42,42,22,30,11,34,41,41,41,41,37,37,41,43,39]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {[%csl Re3,Gg3] This move is Black's most common continuation in the 4.e3 line (4.e3 Bf5 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 Bg6), but here White gets a better version of that line because g3 is more useful than e3.} 7. Nxg6 {we immediately capture on d3 with the idea to continue with Qd3-Bg2-00.} hxg6 8. Qd3 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Yd3c4,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] My recommendation. We protect c4 and are ready for Bg2-00 normal development.} ({I don't like} 8. Qb3 {because after} Qb6 {and it's difficult to fight for an advantage. For example:} 9. c5 Qxb3 10. axb3 Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4] Black is ready for Nb4.} 11. Ra4 {[%cal Ra6b4] we prevent Nb4, but after} Nc7 $11 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gf8e7,Ga7a6] Black will continue with Kd7-Be7-a6 and the position is just equal.}) 8... Nbd7 {In more than 90% of the games Black has played Nbd7, because it's a necessary move sooner or later.} (8... Na6 $6 {[%cal Ga6b4] Black wants to play Nb4, but after} 9. a3 $16 {[%csl Ra6] the knight on a6 is misplaced.}) 9. Bg2 {Now, Black has three main options: Be7-Bd6 or Bb4.} Be7 {[%csl Ge7] this is Black's most sound development.} (9... Qa5 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ga5a6,Ya6c4,Yd7b6] looks strange, but Black's idea could be Qa6-Nb6, creating some pressure against c4.} 10. O-O Qa6 11. b3 {we protect c4, and in the case of} Nb6 {we can continue with} 12. Rb1 $1 {[%csl Gb1,Yb7][%cal Gb1b7] which is a very strong move because once Black will play dxc4, our rook on b1 will be very useful.} dxc4 13. bxc4 Nxc4 14. e4 $36 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gf1c1] e4-Bg5-Rfc1 next. We have the initiative, not just compensation.}) (9... Bd6 $6 {[%csl Rd6] Bd6 looks better placed than on e7, but in reality it's a bad square for its development.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 {[%csl Rd6] Black's bishop on d6 might be misplaced, for example:} Qe7 {standard move, but after} (11... Qa5 {this move is good when Black's bishop is on e7, but not here.} 12. c5 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} Be7 13. b4 $1 $16 {we can develop a very quick queenside play.}) 12. Bg5 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] we are ready for e4, and it's difficult to continue with Black.}) (9... Bb4 {[%cal Re2e4,Gb4c3] Looks strange, but Black usually plays Bb4 with the idea to fight agaisnt e2-e4.} 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 $14 {if Black takes on c3 we can just play with 2 bishops versus 2 knights, and if Black plays Be7 back we just have an extra a3 move (which is for sure useful) compared to the 9...Be7 variation.}) 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1] I feel that this is the most useful move for us.} ({you can also play a normal move like} 11. Bg5 {and after something like} a5 12. Rfd1 a4 13. h4 $14 {the position is very playable and we are slightly better.}) 11... Qa5 {[%cal Ga5a6,Rc1g5,Ya5g5,Yd5c4] This is the only concrete move. Black stops Bg5 (because of dxc4 tactical idea) and also intends to continue with Qa6, creating in this way some pressure against c4.} (11... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Black wants to play a4, but we can prevent it with} 12. b3 $14 {[%cal Rd8a5,Ra5a4] we stop a4, and just play.}) (11... Rc8 {[%csl Rc8] Rc8 is not a useful move, we can play as we wish.} 12. Bf4 $5 $14 (12. h4 $5 $14)) (11... Re8 {normal move. In general, we can play this position in many ways, but I like the following move:} 12. Rb1 $5 {[%csl Gb1] Rb1 is very useful in many cases.} (12. Bg5 {I don't like it now because after for example} Ng4 $5 {I don't want to exchange the bishops.} 13. Bd2 f5 $5 $13 {I don't know what is this.}) (12. h4 $5 {also possible.} Qa5 13. Bg5 $14) 12... a5 13. b3 {[%cal Ra5a4] we stop a4.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6a6] Black wants to place the queen on a6.} 14. Bg5 Qa6 {Matlakov-Volkov.} 15. h4 $5 $14 {Our position is slightly better and also easier to play: exactly what we want to achieve from the 4.g3 Slav.}) 12. Rb1 $5 $146 {[%csl Gh2] My recommendation. Compared to 12.h4, we want to have the same endgame, but with the pawn on h2 and the rook on b1.} ({Let me underline that} 12. Bg5 $2 {is not good because of} dxc4 $15 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ga5g5]}) (12. cxd5 {it's possible, according to the engine, but I think that it's too early for this radical decision.}) (12. h4 {is our normal waiting move, but after} Qa6 $1 13. b3 Nb6 14. c5 Qxd3 15. Rxd3 Nbd7 16. b4 {[%csl Rh4] I prefer to have this endgame with Rb1 instead of h4. Why? First of all, because Rb1 is more useful. Secondly, because Black gets an additional idea against our pawn on h4:} e5 17. e3 e4 18. Rd1 g5 $1 {interesting idea which shows that h4 is not always a useful move for us.} 19. hxg5 Nh7 $13 20. Bh3 {probably White is slightly better, but the position could be very unclear in a practical game.} (20. g6 $6 {looks logical, but it's not good.} Ng5 $1 21. gxf7+ Rxf7 $36 {[%cal Ga8f8,Gd7f6,Gf6g4]}) 20... Rad8 $13) 12... Qa6 {the most forcing move.} ({if Black plays a normal move like} 12... Rfd8 {we can now continue with} 13. h4 {[%cal Gc1g5] now we can play it. Bg5 is our idea.} Rac8 {[%csl Rc8] looks logical, but I am not sure that rook on c8 is good after we play} (13... Qa6 14. b3 Nb6 15. c5 Qxd3 16. Rxd3 Nbd7 17. b4 $14 {[%csl Gb1,Rd8] Rb1 and Rfd8 is a very good inclusion for us compared to the 12.h4 variation.}) 14. c5 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gb2b4] b4 next, and White is definitely slightly better.}) 13. b3 {[%cal Gc1g5]} Nb6 {if not Nb6, we will play Bg5 as usually.} 14. c5 Qxd3 15. Rxd3 Nbd7 16. b4 {[%csl Gb1,Gh2][%cal Rg6g5] our pawn is on h2 compared to the 12.h4 line, and it's good for us. Also our rook on b1 is useful.} e5 17. e3 {good chances for us. Black doesn't have counterplay.} a6 18. Rd1 $14 {for the engine it's only +0,40, but in a real game I feel that the advantage is more. Our plan is a4-b5 and then see. It's a risk-free endgame.} *

