{[%evp 0,38,24,16,16,15,24,45,45,0,16,22,38,43,21,18,3,7,16,8,-2,22,18,37,31,37,97,79,36,23,21,11,30,43,91,24,24,24,11,26,26]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg4 {Black plays Bg4 instead of Bg6 to provoke h3 and g4 before allowing Nxg6-hxg6. White gets the bishop pair but with h3 and g4 included, which could be either a strength or a weakness.} 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 {now Black can play the standard 8...Bg6, or try the concrete moves 8...Ne4 or 8...Nfd7.} (8. Qb3 {also possible, but I prefer 8.g4.} Qb6 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bg2 {playable position, yes, but 8.g4 is more interesting, in my opinion.}) 8... Bg6 {[%cal Gg4g5] The most common continuation. Compared to the 6...Bg6 line, here the inclusion of h3-g4 favors us, mainly due to the concrete g4-g5 idea.} (8... Nfd7 $2 {although this move has been played in a lot of games, it's a very bad direction for Black:} 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7,Rd8b6] the key point is that Black cannot play Qb6 and it's not easy to defend b7.} b6 {looks normal, but after} 10. cxd5 cxd5 (10... Qxh4 11. dxe6 $18) 11. gxh5 Qxh4 12. e4 $1 Nc6 13. Be3 $18 {White has a decisive advantage.}) (8... Ne4 $5 {interesting sideline.} 9. Nxe4 dxe4 (9... Qxh4 $2 {would be a mistake because of} 10. Qb3 $1 Qe7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc5 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rh5][%cal Gc5b7]}) 10. Qb3 {This position has appeared in 12 games, but only once did Black find the only good move} Nd7 $1 (10... Qxh4 $4 11. Qxb7 $18 {Black can resign.}) (10... b6 {is Black's most natural and common continuation, but after} 11. Ng2 Bg6 12. h4 $1 $146 {we have a serious advantage.} h6 (12... h5 13. Nf4 $16) 13. Be3 $16 {[%cal Gg2f4,Ge1c1] Nf4-000 next, with a big lead in the development.}) 11. gxh5 $1 $146 {White's most interesting continuation.} ({after the solid} 11. Ng2 {Black is doing fine, for example:} Bg6 12. h4 h6 13. Nf4 Bh7 14. Bd2 Qc7 15. O-O-O O-O-O $132 (15... b5 $5 $13)) 11... Qxh4 12. Rg1 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gg1g4,Gc1g5,Yg1g7] Rg1 is extremely useful because it prepares Rg4 or Bg5 ideas, and at the same time targets g7.} (12. Qxb7 $6 Rb8 {[%cal Gf8b4] Bb4+ next, and Black is fine:} 13. Qxc6 Bb4+ 14. Kd1 O-O $1 $13 {The engine shows 0.00, but the position is riskier for White than for Black. For instance, at this moment, the only good move for us is 15.a3.}) 12... b6 {probably the best.} (12... Qxh5 $2 13. Qxb7 $1 {now the capture on b7 is good.} Rb8 14. Qxc6 Bb4+ 15. Kd1 O-O 16. Qxe4 $18) (12... Be7 13. h6 $1 gxh6 14. Rg4 Qf6 15. Rxe4 O-O-O 16. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next, and I guess that everybody would take White.}) 13. Be3 Qxh5 14. O-O-O $36 {We have more than full compensation for the pawn, for example:} g6 (14... Rc8 15. Kb1 {Simple move. Now, Black needs to spend a tempo on g7-g6 to complete the development.} (15. Qa4 $5 {deserves attention.}) (15. Rg5 $5) 15... g6 16. Rg5 Qh4 17. d5 $36 {interesting new position and it's difficult to believe that Black will be happy here.}) 15. Bg2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gg2e4]} Nf6 (15... f5 $2 16. c5 $1 $16 {[%csl Re6]}) 16. f3 Bh6 17. fxe4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Black shouldn't allow our e4-e5.} e5 {only move.} 18. Bxh6 Qxh6+ 19. Kb1 {Positionally, Black is doing fine, but he just misses one tempo to consolidate:} O-O (19... Nd7 20. d5 c5 21. Qa4 $16 {[%csl Rd7]}) 20. dxe5 Nh5 21. e6 $1 fxe6 22. c5 $1 Nf4 23. Bf1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e3] e3 next.}) 9. g5 $1 {It's better for White to start with g5 before including the capture on g6.} (9. Nxg6 {is also fine, but after} hxg6 10. g5 ({In the 6...Bg6 variation our move was} 10. Qd3 $2 {but here this is not possible because of} Nxg4 $17) 10... Ng8 $1 $13 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7,Ge7f5] Black will play Bd6-Ne7-Nf6, and the position is unclear.}) 9... Ne4 {This is undoubtedly Black's best option, as exchanging his Nf6 for our Nc3 is more favorable than retreating the knight to a passive square like g8 or d7.} (9... Ng8 $6 {Now, we will play without Nxg6:} 10. Bg2 Ne7 11. O-O Nf5 {standard continuation, and now we can play energetically:} (11... Bh5 $146 {Black's best according to the engine.} 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. e4 $1 $14 {The engine suggests 13...h6 but evaluates the position as +0.50. It’s a new and, at the very least, highly interesting position for us.}) 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. e4 $1 $146 {strong move, after which Black is seriously worse.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 $16 {For example:} Be7 {the engine suggests 14...Bxe4, but Be7 looks as a human move.} 15. Ng3 $1 {big problems for Black's bishop.} Bg6 16. h4 $18 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) (9... Nfd7 $6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. e4 $16 {This position is very bad for Black, but in practice, Black scored three wins and one loss. Therefore, I’ll continue the analysis for one more move:} dxe4 12. Qg4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge1c1] is a strong novelty. We will continue with Bd2-000 and capture on e4 only on the most convenient moment.} ({after the natural} 12. Nxe4 {Black is just slightly worse with} Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Qa5 $14)) 10. Nxg6 {In all ten games that reached this position, White chose 10.Nxg6. You can decide whether to follow this path or explore a new direction, such as 10.Bg2 or 10.Qb3.} (10. Bg2 $5 $146 {deserves attention, and you can use it if you want to have a simple game.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bh5 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. c5 Qxb3 (13... Qc7 $2 14. Bf4 $1 $16) 14. axb3 $14 {The engine evaluates this as only +0.20, but most of us would likely enjoy playing this endgame as White.}) (10. Qb3 $5 $146 {another interesting direction.} Qb6 11. Bg2 Qxb3 12. axb3 Bb4 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Kf1 $14 {I think that it's not so easy to play for Black.}) 10... hxg6 $1 {Black shouldn't fear the Nxe4-dxe4 structure.} (10... Nxc3 $2 {a positionally bad decision.} 11. bxc3 hxg6 12. Qb3 $16 {White has a serious positional advantage.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bg2 ({After the prophylactic} 12. a3 {Black can equalize by playing} c5 $1 $11) 12... Bb4+ $1 $146 {Black's only good continuation is a novelty.} (12... Rh4 $2 {was tried in Millkow-Nikolaidis, but after} 13. Qb3 $1 $16 {[%csl Yh4][%cal Gb3g3,Yg3h4] White has a serious advantage. The main point is that in the case of 13...Qb6, 14.Qg3! is very strong.}) 13. Kf1 {and only now} Rh4 $1 14. Qb3 Na6 {[%csl Rb4] Black's Bb4 looks really misplaced, but the computer holds with Black, for example:} 15. Be3 {the best, according to the engine.} (15. a3 Be7 16. Qxb7 Nc5 $1 17. Qxc6+ Kf8 $44 {Black has good compensation.}) 15... Qe7 {[%cal Ge8c8,Ye7b4,Ye7b7] Black supports b4, b7 and prepares the long castle.} 16. a3 Ba5 $1 {we can for sure play, but I was not able to find an advantage:} (16... Bd6 $2 17. c5 $16 {[%csl Rd6] Black's bishop has to go on b8, and that's certainly not a good square.}) 17. Qc2 O-O-O $1 18. Bxe4 Bb6 19. c5 Bc7 $44 {The position looks good for us, but the engine evaluates it as only +0.15, meaning Black has nearly full compensation for the pawn. In conclusion, you can follow the common 10.Nxg6, where Black must be extremely well-prepared to avoid a much worse position. However, if Black knows everything, starting from the novelty 12...Bb4+, he should be fine. Alternatively, you can choose the more positional alternatives 10.Qb3 or 10.Bg2.} *

