{[%evp 0,39,17,17,24,-8,31,31,32,3,0,0,0,3,47,47,26,30,30,-17,-17,-10,29,19,29,13,10,12,66,57,62,62,51,39,85,85,54,27,40,26,20,19]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 {Black's most common continuation aims to provoke f3 before playing Bg6. While f3 seems a poor inclusion for White positionally (it weakens the structure, and our Bg2 becomes less effective), it can sometimes be turned to our advantage through concrete play.} 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 {Against 6...Be4, we will try to reach an endgame.} (8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Qd3 $6 {This is our reaction against 6...Bg6, but here it doesn't work so well with f3 included, at least because of} c5 $1 $36) 8... Qb6 {This is Black's standard continuation. Now, we have two possible plans.} (8... Qc8 $2 {[%csl Rc8] bad square for Black's queen.} 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. fxe4 {we have good center, good development and 2 bishops.} e5 {only logical move for Black.} 12. dxe5 Ng4 (12... Nfd7 13. e6 $1 fxe6 14. Bg5 Nc5 15. Qc2 $16 {Vaibahav-Keymer.}) 13. e6 $1 {it's important to return the pawn on our terms. Normally, I would start the analysis here, but I must mention a possibility showed by the engine:} Qxe6 $1 {engine-style move.} (13... fxe6 14. Be2 Ne5 15. c5 $1 $18 {terrible for Black.}) 14. Qxb7 {looks lost for Black, but} Bc5 $1 {only move.} 15. Qxa8 O-O 16. Qb7 Nd7 $1 $146 {we have an extra rook, but the engine shows +1,00, which means that we are better but we should be careful:} (16... Qf6 $2 {was played in Alexiadis-Le, but after} 17. Be2 $1 Qf2+ 18. Kd1 Rd8+ 19. Kc2 $18 {Black is lost.}) 17. Qb3 {I will not comment the next moves because I'm just following the engine's first line, which is made by a lot of only moves for Black:} Bf2+ 18. Ke2 Nc5 19. Qc2 Bd4 $1 (19... Qxc4+ $4 20. Kf3 $18) 20. h3 Nf2 21. Rh2 Qxc4+ 22. Ke1 $1 (22. Kf3 Qxf1 $11) 22... Nfd3+ 23. Bxd3 Nxd3+ 24. Kf1 $1 Nxc1+ 25. Kg2 Nd3 26. Rd1 Ne5 27. Qa4 Bxc3 28. Qxc4 Nxc4 29. Rc1 $1 $16) (8... Qd7 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Rb8d7] It seems a bit odd because the queen is occupying the d7 square, which would normally be useful for the knight.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Be3 $1 {[%cal Rc6c5,Ye3d4] We protect d4 and stop c5.} (10. e3 $6 c5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next.}) 10... Be7 (10... Bd6 {Bd6 is worse placed than Be7.} 11. Bf2 $16 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge1c1,Ye2e4] 000, and eventually e4 next.}) 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O $14 {I see no reason to doubt that White is at least slightly better.}) 9. c5 {I slightly prefer 9.c5, but 9.Nxg6 is also a good option, especially if you’re aiming for a more complex position.} (9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. e3 {leads to more complicated positions, for example:} Nbd7 11. Bd2 {we actually transposed in a line from the 4.e3 Slav.} Be7 12. Kf2 $5 {this is a very playable direction.}) 9... Qxb3 {Black must exchange queens.} ({Black sholdn't retreat the queen:} 9... Qc7 $2 10. Bf4 Qc8 {Now we can use our huge lead in development:} 11. e4 $1 {we are seriously better, for example:} Be7 (11... dxe4 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. fxe4 $18 {Black is simply lost.}) 12. Bd6 $1 $16 {at least advantage, but maybe it's just winning for us.}) 10. axb3 {[%csl Ye4,Gf3,Yg4] In this endgame, the pawn on f3 is useful as it controls the critical e4 and g4 squares. Occasionally, we might consider playing e2-e4 or g3-g4, depending on the specific situation.} Na6 {Black's most common continuation. Na6 gives Black the option of either the concrete Nb4 or the positional Nc7. From c7, the knight controls the key b5 square, making it harder for us to break through with b4-b5.} (10... Nbd7 $2 {bad move:} 11. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5] we are ready for b5, and Black cannot stop it.} e5 (11... a6 12. b5 $16) 12. e3 Be7 13. b5 O-O 14. b4 $1 $16 {[%cal Yb5c6,Yb7c6,Gb4b5] we will continue with bxc6-bxc6 and play b5 once again.}) (10... Bc2 {concrete move.} 11. b4 h6 $1 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Gc2h7] Black secures the h7 square for his bishop.} (11... Na6 $6 12. b5 Nb4 13. e3 $14) 12. Ng2 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4] We improve our knight, and also prepare Bf4.} ({no need to play} 12. b5 {when Black's knight is still on b8, because after} Be7 13. bxc6 $6 {Black can recapture with the knight} Nxc6 $15 {Remember that usually the b4-b5 idea is strong when Black's knight is already on d7.}) 12... Be7 {for sure this is Black's most normal move.} 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Kd2 (14. e4 {don't go for this concrete idea, because Black will be fine in the end:} dxe4 15. Ne3 Bd3 $13) 14... Bh7 15. g4 {[%cal Gh2h4,Re6e5,Ge2e3] We can continue with e3-h4 and the key point is that it's not easy for Black to prepare e6-e5.} Nfd7 {only move that allows Black to play e5, but at the cost of some development problems:} (15... Nbd7 16. e3 $14 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gb4b5] with Black's knight on d7 we will definitely consider b4-b5 on the next move.}) 16. e3 e5 17. Bg3 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1e2,Yg2e1,Ye1d3,Yb4b5] It's not easy to play for Black, while we have a lot of ways to improve the position.} (17. dxe5 $2 a5 $1 $15)) 11. Nxg6 {it's a good moment to capture on g6.} hxg6 12. e3 {simple move, and it's my recommendation.} (12. Ra4 $5 {deserves attention. It was played by Carlsen.}) ({I don't want to play} 12. e4 {because after} Nb4 $13 {[%csl Rd4] White must think also about the weak pawn on d4.}) 12... Nb4 $5 $146 {nobody has tried it, but it might be Black's best continuation.} (12... Nc7 {solid option.} 13. b4 {normal continuation.} (13. Kf2 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2a5] you can also consider to play without including b3-b4. Why? Maybe sometimes you will have Bd2-Ba5 idea.}) 13... a6 14. Be2 {This is not an endgame where you need to have a super-strong opening preparation. You can just play it, and it's risk-free. Yes, Black is solid, but he has almost zero winning chances, and you can have a long game.} (14. Kf2 $5 {[%cal Gf2g2] Kg2 next, it's another idea.}) 14... Be7 15. O-O $36 {[%cal Ge3e4] at the right moment, we will play e4, but very often we will need to prepare it carefully.}) 13. Kf2 (13. Ra4 a5 $132 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gb7b6] Nd7-b6 next, and Black is fine.}) 13... Nd7 14. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc3d1] we can already consider a move like Nd1, after which Black will have huge problems with the knight on b4.} b6 $1 {only move.} 15. cxb6 Nxb6 16. Ba6 $5 {usually we play for two bishops, but now it's a concrete case and it's more important to stop a7-a5, which would consolidate a lot Black's position.} Nxa6 (16... Rb8 17. Be2 $14 {[%csl Ra7]}) 17. Rxa6 Kd7 18. Na2 $5 {[%cal Ga2c1,Gc1d3] we want Nc1-Nd3.} (18. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh1a1] also deserves attention, just with the idea of continuing with Rha1.}) 18... c5 $1 {the best, according to the engine.} 19. Nc1 cxd4 20. exd4 $14 {[%cal Gc1d3] Nd3 next, and Black still faces some practical problems.} *

