{[%evp 0,47,18,24,24,-8,31,31,32,0,0,2,38,32,46,42,43,44,48,48,44,38,48,35,29,28,27,7,14,20,34,34,44,55,43,47,52,47,85,84,74,92,90,68,66,64,69,80,62,79]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 dxc4 {interesting line, different in nature compared to the previous three that we have seen.} 7. Nxf5 {we must capture Black's bishop.} (7. e3 Bd3 $11 {Black is immediately fine.}) 7... exf5 8. e3 {[%cal Gf1c4] Our next move will be Bxc4.} Nbd7 {most common continuation.} ({Black shouldn't defend c4 by playing} 8... b5 $2 {because after it, he is not in time to defend his queenside pawns.} 9. Bg2 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc3b5] Black needs to defend b5.} a6 (9... b4 10. Na4 $16 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd1c2,Gc2c4] 00-Qc2-Qxc4 next. The main point is that Black doesn't have the light square bishop to defend c4.}) (9... Bb4 10. a4 $16 {Black's queenside is collapsing.}) 10. O-O Bd6 11. Qc2 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gc2f5]} g6 12. a4 {Black cannot protect his queenside pawns, and after} b4 13. Nb1 $16 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4] we will continue with Nd2-Nxc4, with a big positional advantage.}) (8... g6 $5 {has been tried only six times, but it's a very sound continuation.} 9. Bxc4 Bg7 {we can play in different ways, but I like} 10. Qb3 $5 Qc7 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Yc7b7,Gb8d7] defends c7 and, compared to 10...Qe7, Black will be able to develop with Nbd7.} (10... Qe7 {[%cal Rb8d7,Gb3b7] the problem of Qe7, compared with 10...Qc7, is that Black will not be able to play Nbd7 later.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Bd2 {it's not easy for Black to complete the development, and after} b5 13. Be2 Nbd7 14. Rfc1 $14 {we definitely have some pressure.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Bd2 Nbd7 13. Rac1 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc4f1,Yd2e1] Our position is slightly better and easier to play. We can continue, for example, with Rfd1-Bf1-Be1. After the logical moves} Nb6 14. Be2 Rfe8 15. Rfd1 Rad8 (15... Ne4 $2 {is a mistake for concrete reasons:} 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. d5 $1 $16) 16. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5] we can consider a5.} Nbd5 (16... a5 $2 {not possible because of} 17. Nb5 $18 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2a5]}) 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bf3 $14 {we maintain a certain pressure.}) (8... Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8] Compared to the mainline 8...Nbd7, after 8...Bd6 Black's priority is to castle.} 9. Bxc4 O-O {now, we have two possible plans.} 10. O-O {positional continuation. I prefer this over 10.Qf3, but it's up to you to choose.} (10. Qf3 $5 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg3g4] is an ambitious continuation that was also tried by Magnus Carlsen. White's idea is to play h3-g4.} g6 11. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4] we are ready for g4, and Black should be very accurate.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gc6c5,Ye7b7] very strong move because it concretely stops g4. In my opinion, the position is now playable but equal, but you can try to find some other idea if you like it.} (11... c5 $2 {is a standard reaction, but it's not good here simply because of} 12. Qxb7 $16) (11... Nbd7 {standard natural move, but it allows} 12. g4 $1 $16 {after this move Black faces serious problems.}) 12. O-O {is a normal move, but after it} (12. g4 $6 {is not so good now because of} c5 $1 $13 {and the position is very unclear.}) 12... Nbd7 13. g4 $132 {[%csl Rf1,Gg4] we managed to play g4, but our rook is already on f1, and not on h1. The position is playable, but we don't have an advantage.}) 10... Nbd7 {we can play it in many ways, but I like} 11. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5] we want to play a4-a5, which could give us some important space on the queenside.} (11. f3 $6 {is premature because of} c5 $1 $13) 11... a5 {it looks logical for Black to stop a4-a5, but now} 12. f3 $5 {[%cal Ge3e4] becomes more interesting because after the standard} c5 {[%csl Ga4,Ra5][%cal Gc3b5] thanks to a4-a5 inclusion, we have the b5 square for our knight.} 13. Nb5 $14) 9. Bxc4 Nb6 {necessary inclusion for Black.} (9... Bd6 $2 {would be a mistake now because of} 10. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rf7][%cal Gc4f7,Gb3b7]}) (9... g6 $2 10. Qb3 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Rf7][%cal Gc4f7,Rb3b7]}) 10. Bb3 {[%csl Gb3] This is a good square for our bishop. Now, Black must decide how to continue the development.} ({I don't like} 10. Bd3 {because after} g6 $132 {[%csl Rd3] Our bishop on d3 doesn't stay well.}) 10... Qd7 {[%csl Yf8][%cal Ge8c8] This is Black's most common continuation. Qd7 is a useful move, and it doesn't reveal Black's development plans.} (10... g6 {if Black wants to play with g6, then it's better for him to do it at move 8, because now} 11. f3 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. e4 $14 {White has a sensible advantage.}) (10... Be7 {solid but slightly passive.} 11. O-O O-O 12. f3 {[%cal Ge3e4] we can play for e4.} Qd7 (12... c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga1d1,Yg1g2] Bd2-Rad1 next. We can play thanks to our pair of bishops.}) 13. e4 Rad8 {[%csl Rd4] Black tries to create some counterplay against d4.} (13... fxe4 $2 {is a bad inclusion:} 14. fxe4 Rad8 15. e5 $16 {[%cal Gf1f8] thanks to fxe4-fxe4, our rook on f1 becomes strong.}) 14. e5 ({the normal} 14. Be3 $6 {is a mistake because after} fxe4 $13 {[%cal Rf3e4,Gf6g4] we cannot capture fxe4 because of Ng4.}) 14... Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7,Yb6d5] Black plays Ne8 with the idea of continuing with Nc7-Nbd5.} (14... Nfd5 15. Qe2 {we can continue with useful moves, and after the critical} ({not} 15. Qc2 $2 {because of} Nb4 $1 $15) 15... c5 (15... Bb4 16. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Rd5b4] now Qc2 is good because Black doesn't have Nb4.}) 16. dxc5 Bxc5+ 17. Kg2 $14 {we can hope for a small advantage thanks to our two bishops.}) 15. Be3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ga1d1] we can continue with Qe2-Rad1, for example:} Nc7 16. Qe2 Nbd5 17. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Yg3g4,Ye3c1,Yg1h1] Black is solid but has no active plan. We can slowly improve our position (Bc1-Kh1) and maybe one day g3-g4 will be an interesting idea.}) (10... Bd6 {normal development, but we can once again proceed with the f3-e4 plan.} 11. f3 O-O $146 {the best continuation for Black.} ({the standard reaction} 11... c5 $6 {is not so good here.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. Ke2 $14 {we can play a long endgame with the two bishops.}) (11... Qd7 12. e4 $1 Bb4 {Kowalski-Nasuta.} 13. O-O O-O 14. e5 Nfd5 15. Qc2 $14) 12. O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] we are now ready for e4, and after} (12. e4 $6 {is now premature because of} fxe4 13. fxe4 c5 $1 $13) (12. Qd3 $5 Qd7 13. Bd2 $36 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next. It's an interesting extra option.}) 12... c5 $1 {Black's best move.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Qc2 {we transpose in the 10...Be7 variation.}) 11. f3 {[%cal Ge3e4] I suggest to be consistent with the f3-e4 plan.} h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] This is Black's best continuation. The idea is to create a fast counterplay on the kingside with h5-h4.} (11... Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. e4 {transposes to 10...Be7.}) (11... Bd6 12. e4 {transposes to 10...Bd6.}) 12. Bd2 (12. h4 $2 {is not good because after} Bd6 $15 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gd6g3] we have problems with the g3 pawn.}) 12... h4 13. g4 $5 $146 {this is my recommendation. It's a very interesting pawn sacrifice:} (13. gxh4 {possible direction, but after} Be7 14. Qe2 a5 $1 {Black has a good game, for example:} 15. a3 a4 16. Bc2 f4 $1 $13 {Bjerre-Horvath, 2021.}) 13... fxg4 (13... f4 $2 14. e4 Qxd4 15. Bxf4 $16 {White has a big positional advantage.}) 14. fxg4 Qxg4 (14... Nxg4 $6 15. Qf3 $36 {problems for Black.}) 15. Qxg4 Nxg4 16. Ke2 $36 {[%cal Gh1g1,Ga1f1] We can continue with Rhg1-Raf1 and create a lot of pressure.} Nf6 (16... Rd8 {allows} 17. Ne4 $36 {that's why the engine starts with 16...Nf6.}) 17. Rhg1 {[%csl Rf8] it's not easy to understand how to continue with Black. Bf8 cannot move because of g7, Ke7 cannot move because of f7, g7-g6 cannot be played because it would weaken the 'f' file...} Rd8 18. Raf1 {Now, the engine plays Rd7 or Nbd5.} Nbd5 (18... Rd7 {[%cal Gd7f7] Black defends f7.} 19. Be1 $5 $44 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3,Yh3h4] sometimes we can think about Rf3-Rh3-Rxh4 to restore the material equality and play a position with the two bishops.}) 19. Nxd5 (19. e4 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 19... Nxd5 (19... cxd5 $2 20. Rf5 $16 {[%cal Gf5e5]}) 20. e4 Nf6 21. Be3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gf1f5,Ye3d4] we have a lot of ideas to increase the pressure.} Nxe4 $1 {Black's best, according to the engine, but I am not sure that our opponent will feel comfortable:} (21... Rd7 22. Bc2 $36 {more than full compensation.}) 22. Bxf7+ Ke7 23. Kd3 Nf6 24. Bb3 $44 {[%cal Ge3f4,Gf4e5] Bf4-Be5 next. We have for sure full compensation, maybe something more.} *

