1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 (4... g6 {Black can start with this move also and capture on the next, but White has some extra options, that's why it's more likely you will see the 4...dxc4 move order.} 5. Bg2 (5. cxd5 {is one extra option Black should consider.}) 5... dxc4 {Transposition.}) 5. Bg2 g6 {I used to play this line frequently as Black, considering it a solid yet ambitious choice. I contributed significantly to its theoretical development through games against strong young players. However, White has many ideas, and success with Black requires deep positional understanding beyond mere theory. In short, this is a line for deep chess.} 6. O-O {Castle is anyway a useful move for us.} (6. Na3 {is not great because of} b5 $13 {[%csl Ra3] And the knight can be sometimes misplaced.}) 6... Bg7 7. a4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Yc6c5] The starting position of this Unit. White's main idea is to play Na3-Nxc4, after which we are slightly better.} (7. Ne5 {is even worse than before, because of the strong reply} Ng4 $1 $132 {[%csl Rd4] And White has some issues defending the d4-pawn.}) 7... Ne4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ye4d6] The most important line for Black. The idea is simple: to meet Na3 with Nd6, protecting c4. White has two directions: Qc2 or Nc3.} (7... Be6 {is of course met with} 8. Ng5 {[%cal Ge6d7,Gb1a3] Tempo against the bishop, if the bishop goes back, we continue with Na3.} Bd5 9. e4 {A thematic position arises after} h6 10. exd5 hxg5 {And in this concrete case} 11. d6 $1 $146 {is the strongest continuation.} exd6 (11... Qxd6 12. Na3 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4] Nxc4 next, White is slightly better.}) 12. Re1+ {important intermezzo.} Kf8 13. Bxg5 {Pawn down, but huge compensation.} d5 {If Black consolidates everything, we can play Catalan style with} 14. b3 cxb3 15. Qxb3 $36 {And it's not only compensation, but also huge initiative.}) (7... h6 {[%cal Rf3g5,Gc8e6] was played in the game Svane-Sevian. Black's idea is to prepare Be6, without allowing Ng5.} 8. Re1 $5 $146 {Since Black played an useful, but slow move, I also like to play the useful Re1.} (8. Na3 Be6 9. Qc2 {is how the game continued, but after} Na6 $132 {Black should be more or less fine here.}) 8... O-O {Of course, Black can play somehow, but after} (8... Be6 9. e4 $16 {[%cal Gb1a3,Gd1c2,Ga3c4] is the idea, of course, and the point is that the knight doesn't have to go c3 automatically, it can go to a3 also.}) 9. Na3 $14 {[%csl Ge1,Rh6] We have the 7...0-0 line, but with the moves h6 and Re1 included, which favors White, engine also agrees, so we can stop here.}) (7... c5 $5 {[%csl Ga4] The immediate c5 was tried in the game Donchenko-Zubov, but if you think about it, it is a Grunfeld position where White has the extra move a4, which can benefit us.} 8. dxc5 $146 {I suggest to capture.} O-O 9. Na3 c3 {is Black's typical reaction, now we can play in the same style as in the Gruenfeld line.} (9... Na6 {[%csl Ra2,Ga4] It's not the main line with the pawn on a2, but here it is the strongest move.} 10. c6 bxc6 11. Nxc4 {Black can argue that the a4 inclusion is not the best for us right now, but also Na6 was not the most critical line, so White is slightly better after, for example:} Be6 12. Qxd8 Rfxd8 13. Na5 Bd5 14. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rc6] Pressure on the c6 square.}) 10. Nb5 {Good move.} Na6 11. Nxc3 Nxc5 12. Be3 {This line exists with the pawn on a2.} Nce4 {or Nfe4 is Black's usual reaction, and here we can go for} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5] And actually the pawn on a4 now (compared to the line where the pawn is on a2) is very useful. White can continue to grab space with a5, for example. Engine also agrees: with the pawn on a2: 0.00 evaluation, with the pawn on a4: +0.35 evalution.}) (7... O-O {will be analyzed in Position 1 of this Unit.}) 8. Qc2 {is my main recommendation, and we will study it in "Position 2" of this Unit.} (8. Nc3 $5 {is a very interesting move, it has been played a lot against me also.} Nd6 {is the best line.} (8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 {White has very good play.} O-O 10. Ba3 {It is not so easy to develop the pieces with Black.} Nd7 11. Qc2 $36 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1d1,Gc2a2,Ye2e4,Yf3d2,Yd2c4] White can slowly improve the pieces, try to capture on c4, and play with a good center. It looks unpleasant for Black.}) 9. e4 Bg4 $1 {Very important move.} (9... O-O {If castle, White has} 10. e5 Ne8 {is the best for the engine, but} (10... Nf5 $6 {is met with} 11. g4 $1 {Typical move.} Nh6 12. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh6] The knight is misplaced on h6, White has a serious advantage.}) 11. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga4a5,Ge2c4] White is at least slightly better.}) 10. Be3 {Main line.} (10. e5 $2 {would be a mistake now, because of} Nf5 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Gg4][%cal Gf5d4] and thanks to the move Bg4, Black has pressure against d4.}) 10... Qc8 {I was usually starting with this move.} 11. Qe2 {Main move.} (11. Qd2 $5 {is an interesting sideline.} Na6 12. Nh4 {[%cal Gf2f4] is the idea behind the previous move. It has only been tried in correspondence chess. So it can be a valid alternative.} Bh3 {The best move for the engine.} (12... O-O {is the most logical for Black, but it is very dangerous after} 13. f4 f6 14. f5 gxf5 15. h3 Bh5 16. Nxf5 {I didn't like this position for Black, White has a lot of tries.} Nxf5 17. exf5 $40 {[%cal Gf1f4,Gf4h4,Ga1f1] White can play for an attack.}) 13. Qe2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {White can try to play this position, for example:} O-O 15. e5 Nf5 16. Nxf5 Qxf5 17. Qxc4 $132 {The position is definetely playable.}) 11... O-O 12. Rad1 Na6 {I played this position 2 times, here White has a very interesting move:} 13. h3 $5 {An amazing move, it was played against me for the first time in 2021.} Bxh3 14. Bxh3 Qxh3 15. e5 {[%cal Rd6f5,Gf3g5] is the idea, where Nf5 is impossible because of Ng5.} Ne8 {Black needs to know, but if he knows, he is fine.} 16. d5 {Dardha-Mishra, Saint Louis 2023.} Nec7 17. dxc6 {is the best, but Black is in time to equalize.} bxc6 18. Qxc4 c5 $11 {Strong move, the position is fine for Black. White has some tries, but not more.}) *

