{[%evp 0,14,22,20,20,-14,40,40,40,14,1,4,14,18,9,3,25]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. a4 O-O 8. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] Nxc4 is our idea, and if we manage it, White should be slightly better.} Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4] Black's other idea is to use the b4 square.} (8... Nbd7 $6 {For example, after a passive move, White can just take:} 9. Nxc4 Nb6 {is a typical plan and now it's important to not trade the knights.} 10. Ncd2 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] Even stronger than Nce5.} a5 {Black should stop a5 himself.} 11. e4 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd1c2,Gb2b3,Yc1b2,Yc1a3] Good center, typical advantage for White. The knight on b6 is misplaced.}) (8... a5 {is not in time to consolidate the b4 square.} 9. Nxc4 Na6 10. Bd2 $36 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga6b4,Gd1b3,Rc4a5] The a5 pawn is in serious danger, and after Nb4-Qb3, the threat is renewed.}) (8... Be6 {A concrete move, with the idea to defend the c4 pawn.} 9. Ng5 $1 {Important move, otherwise we are not in time.} Bd5 {In case of other moves, White can just take on c4 and be happy.} 10. e4 h6 11. exd5 hxg5 {Now d6 doesn't make any sense, because the king is already on g8, so White can just capture:} 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. d5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga3c4,Gc1g5] The best move. Now we are in a concrete position with 22 games, pawn down for now, but 2 pawns are hanging.} Nb4 {[%csl Rd5] The first thing to do is to evaluate what happens if Black goes for the d5 pawn.} 14. Nxc4 {We can capture on c4 first.} Nbxd5 (14... Rc8 {doesn't change the evaluation.} 15. Qb3 Nfxd5 {Black can try to recapture with the f-knight, but that's also quite risky.} 16. Bxg5 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1d1] The knights can be also misplaced. White is at least slightly better.}) 15. Bxg5 $14 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Gd1b3,Gf1e1,Gh2h4,Yh4h5] Here we can say with confindence that White is slightly better, because of the pair of bishops. Qb3-Re1-h4 can be useful continuation moves.}) 9. Nxc4 Be6 {Black usually develops first.} (9... Nb4 $6 {Here it is quite premature.} 10. Qb3 a5 11. Bd2 $36 {[%cal Gc4a5] Nxa5 is already a threat, Black faces concrete problems.}) (9... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Ge4d6] Very rare move, played only in 5 correspondence games. Black's idea is to save time on Be6, and sometimes play Nd6, from where the knight is very good.} 10. b3 {We can continue our development.} Nb4 (10... Nd6 $6 {There is no reason to go immediately, better for Black to wait for the knight to be attacked.} 11. Bb2 $14 {Slightly better for White.}) 11. Nfe5 Nd6 {And before Black plays a7-a5 himself, White can go} 12. a5 $146 {to stop the consolidation of the b4 square. Normally, it is a slightly better position for White, but the engine is not so optimistic, only +0.25. We have to consider however, that the line is very rare and White still has a very pleasant game. A sample line could be:} Be6 {is the best, but after} 13. Ra4 $5 $14 {Not the only move, but asks an important question. Black has to be very careful and evaluate on every move.}) 10. b3 {And only now Black can consider jumping on b4, but other options exist.} Bd5 {[%cal Gd5h1] The main move. It was played in the game Van Foreest-Sarana, Olympiad 2024. If it is Black to move, they can play c5 and just be fine, because now they control the important diagonal, that's why White should play} (10... Nb4 {And now it is important to start with} 11. Ng5 $1 {Useful tempo.} ({Not} 11. Ba3 $6 {,because} a5 $11 {and Black is just fine.}) 11... Bxc4 (11... Bd5 {runs into} 12. e4 $16 {White is much better.}) 12. bxc4 $14 {[%cal Ga1b1] Two bishops, slightly better for White.}) (10... c5 {From structural point of view, the most critical move, but} 11. Ba3 $1 {is strong here.} Rc8 {Black can support c5, but now we open another diagonal.} 12. Ng5 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gg2b7] Problems with b7.} Bd5 13. e4 {White is better, for example:} Bxc4 14. bxc4 cxd4 15. e5 $18 {[%cal Ge5e6] e6 next, White is winning.}) 11. Ba3 $1 {[%cal Rc6c5] With the idea to prevent c5.} Rc8 {Sarana insists, but} 12. Rc1 {Very good and useful move.} Nc7 {Sarana gave up on c5, but when this happens, White has an advantage with any move, for example:} (12... c5 $2 {is premature, because of} 13. Ne3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd4c5,Rd5e6,Rf3g5] With big advantage for White.}) 13. Ne3 $5 {is an interesting idea.} Be4 14. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3d2] A good tempo move, the threat is Nd2, after which the bishop will feel very uncomfortable in the center.} Bxf3 15. exf3 $14 {[%csl Ga3,Gh3][%cal Gf3f4,Gf4f5] The structure is ruined, but the 2 bishops are very strong, and White can continue with f4-f5, because it is not easy to play e6.} *

