{[%evp 0,49,21,20,15,10,33,33,33,2,-1,-1,4,2,-6,-10,-1,0,0,7,12,-8,25,0,16,16,24,9,9,-5,-5,-5,-2,-4,39,35,29,37,43,43,37,37,28,33,33,0,19,22,38,23,24,27]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. a4 Ne4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ye4d6] The most important line for Black. The idea is simple: to meet Na3 with Nd6, protecting c4. White has two directions: Qc2 or Nc3.} 8. Qc2 {is my main recommendation.} Nd6 {Black is ready for Bf5. So White should not ignore it.} 9. e4 {We play for the strong center.} ({If White ignores,} 9. Na3 {then} Bf5 {is very annoying to meet.} 10. Qc3 O-O $11 {Black is very fine.}) ({Not} 9. Nbd2 {, because we don't want to take on c4 immediately, because if Black exchanges a pair of knights, positionally it's fine.} O-O 10. Nxc4 {Now Black can throw in an intermezzo:} Bf5 11. Qc3 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 $11 {Black has no problems.}) 9... Na6 {is the best move for Black.} (9... Bg4 {If Black plays in the same way as against 8.Nc3, now it makes no sense, because the queen is not pinned.} 10. Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Gc2] h3 next, and White is definitely slightly better.} Qc8 11. e5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd6] And the knight doesn't have good squares.}) (9... O-O {looks like a normal move, but it is not so precise.} 10. Na3 {We can also finish development.} Na6 11. Rd1 {Remember, that changing knights is not our intention.} Nb4 12. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge4e5,Ga3c4] Our idea could be either Bd2, or e5 followed by Nxc4. For example:} Bg4 (12... Nd3 {Now we should play} 13. e5 {to attack d6 and capture on c4.} Nxc1 {is the most logical move.} 14. Raxc1 Ne8 {The best move.} (14... Nf5 $2 {is bad because after} 15. g4 $1 Nh6 16. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh6] The knight is very misplaced on h6.}) 15. Ne1 $146 {is a very precise move. Nxc4 is not running away.} (15. Nxc4 {has been played in all of the games.} Bh6 $13 {[%cal Ge8c7] Engine idea. So we can improve on this.}) 15... Bh6 16. f4 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ga3c4,Ge1d3,Gd3c5] This is our idea.}) 13. Nxc4 {In this concrete moment we can take immediately, because we have a fantastic version.} a5 {White has many ways to play this position.} (13... Nxc4 14. Qxc4 a5 15. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Gd1,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4] All of our pieces are developed, Black faces serious positional problems.}) 14. Nce5 $5 {looks very interesting, to unpin.} Be6 15. Bf4 Qb6 {has been played in almost all the games that reached this position.} 16. Ng5 {is an ambitious, but complicated line.} (16. Rac1 $5 $14 {If you don't want to play complicated, this is a good way. White keeps all pieces on the board, with good center, so White should be happy. For the engine, it is +0.50.}) 16... Bc8 17. Bf1 {This is a computer line, but nowadays, every line is a computer line. The idea is to play for an attack, and very important that} f6 {is met with} 18. Nc4 $1 $40 {Important intermezzo.}) 10. Na3 {Standard plan.} Nb4 {Black jumps in with the knight, trying to save a move on 00.} 11. Qc3 $5 {In this concrete case, this is the most interesting option for White.} (11. Qe2 {If we play in the same way, after} Nd3 {The fact that Rd1 and 00 are not on the board favors Black.} 12. e5 $6 {is not strong now, because of} Nf5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rf5d4] And the d4 pawn is not protected by the rook on d1.}) 11... a5 {Most logical move.} (11... Nd3 {makes no sense now, of course, because the queen is on a better square.} 12. e5 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4] Capture on c4 next, with an advantage.}) 12. e5 {This is a very important position. I analyzed it a lot from the Black side also. But I will show you the most interesting directions for White.} Nd5 $5 {was my idea, it is a rarer move, but in my opinion, stronger than Nf5.} (12... Nf5 $6 {is the most natural move, but I think it is dubious.} 13. g4 {Typical move.} Nh6 14. h3 {[%csl Rh6] The knight on h6 is misplaced.} Nd5 (14... O-O 15. Nxc4 f5 {Black tries to get the knight back into the game, but White can just play:} 16. exf6 exf6 17. Re1 Nf7 {Black reorganized his pieces.} 18. Bd2 {White's idea is Qb3.} Nd5 19. Qb3 $36 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gb3g8,Ga1c1,Gg2f1,Gf1c4,Gf3h2] The position is unpleasant for Black to play, it is definitely pressure thanks to the weakening of the diagonal.}) 15. Qc2 {Key idea.} O-O 16. Nxc4 f5 {In case of f5, we can change the reaction:} 17. g5 $146 {We close the kingside. I also had training games here, and can say that it is much easier to play with White.} (17. exf6 {If we play in the same way,} exf6 $13 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Yc2b3] The queen on c2 is misplaced, White can lose a tempo to improve it, but it is not the same.}) 17... Nf7 18. Bd2 {[%cal Gf1e1] The position was never tried in practice, and I was thinking to play it from the Black side, because the engine shows +0.40, but maybe it is interesting. In reality, it is very difficult to play with Black, because White will just slowly improve the position.} f4 {[%cal Gc8f5] is problably the best plan in the positon.} 19. h4 {Useful move.} Bf5 20. Qb3 {How to play for Black? Very difficult to say.} Qd7 {Normal move.} (20... b6 {If Black defends a5 and b7, after} 21. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rc6] The b and c pawns are vulnerable, and engine says that Black should absolutely find Qc8, already not an easy move.}) 21. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Ra5] At some moment, it will not be easy to find moves with Black. Also the a5 pawn is quite weak, for the engine it's not hanging, but for a human, who knows?}) 13. Qc2 {is the most interesting move, and now Black's idea is} (13. Qe1 {Some may think that it is better to avoid the tempo of Bf5, but it is not so easy.} Nf5 14. g4 {Now we play in the same way as after 12...Nf5.} Nh6 15. h3 O-O 16. Nxc4 {[%csl Re1] It is almost the same position, but I don't like the queen on e1.} f5 17. g5 Nf7 18. Bd2 b6 {[%csl Re1] The queen on e1 is clearly misplaced.} 19. Qd1 {White can lose a tempo, but as usual, losing a tempo it is not the same anymore.} e6 20. Qb3 Ba6 $132 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gg7f8] Black is in time to organize their own counterplay, and Black is fine.}) 13... Bf5 {[%cal Gd6c8] Tempo move, and the knight can go to c8.} (13... Nf5 14. g4 {transposes to 12...Nf5.}) 14. Qd1 {is my recommendation.} (14. Qd2 $5 {is better against Nc8. But engine shows} c3 $1 {is a strong tempo now. And Black should be fine in the complications.} (14... Nc8 $6 {is maybe not so strong now, because after} 15. Nxc4 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc4a5] There are some small problems with the pawn on a5.} Ncb6 $2 {drops a5.} 16. Nxa5 $14) 15. Qe2 $146 {I thought about this move, and it is also a novelty.} (15. bxc3 {If White captures,} Ne4 {The knight found another square.} 16. Qb2 Nexc3 $11 {It's a new and interesting position, but it seems that Black is in time to equalize.} 17. Bd2 Nxa4 18. Qxb7 $11 {I don't know if it is White or Black who is in time, probably just equal.}) 15... Nc8 {is the best.} (15... cxb2 $6 {is met with} 16. Qxb2 {White has for sure good play here.} Nc8 17. Qxb7 $14 {Definitely slightly better for White.}) 16. bxc3 Nxc3 17. Qb2 {I tried to analyze this position:} Nxa4 18. Qxb7 Ncb6 19. Qxc6+ Bd7 20. Qe4 Bf5 21. Qh4 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gf3g5] I think Black has good play here, but I am not sure about full equality, because White wants to play Bh6-Ng5.} h6 $13 {The position is complicated, but I was a bit scary to go for this position with Black. White should be the slightliest bit better.}) 14... Nc8 {Black's idea.} (14... Ne4 $4 {Now it just loses a piece.} 15. Qe1 {[%cal Gg3g4] Not the only move, but the strongest.} h5 16. Nh4 $18 {Black can resign.}) 15. Nxc4 {Now Black should definitely play} Ncb6 {Black develops the passive knight, only 1 email game here.} (15... O-O $6 {is too slow.} 16. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Rc8b6] Black is not in time to develop, and the knight is very misplaced.}) 16. Ne3 $5 {is the most interesting idea.} Nxe3 17. fxe3 {We take with the f pawn.} Be4 {If Black wants to exchange the bishops, we should also be happy.} (17... O-O {The most logical.} 18. Ng5 {[%cal Ge3e4,Yg5e4] Sometimes we have e4 ideas, sometimes Ne4 ideas.} h6 {The most likely move.} 19. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2] It's +0.31 for the engine, but it also looks unpleasant to play with Black, from human point of view.}) 18. Ng5 {Tempo move.} Bxg2 19. Kxg2 O-O 20. e4 {[%csl Rb6,Gd4,Ge4,Ge5] White has a very good center.} h6 21. Nf3 c5 {is the best reaction for the engine.} 22. d5 Nd7 {This was also my preparation with Black.} 23. h4 $5 {Maybe this is interesting, with idea to play Bf4 without allowing g5.} (23. Bf4 {The problem is} g5 {But it also needs to be analyzed. Some sacrifices exist.} 24. Bxg5 {Black should carefully analyze this position.} hxg5 25. Nxg5 {Qh5 is a serious threat.} Qb6 {Only move.} 26. d6 {White should play this, now Black needs to find} f6 $1 $11 {But it ends in 0.00. Anyway it is an important line.}) 23... Qb6 {looks natural, but after} (23... Nxe5 {drops the h6 pawn.} 24. Nxe5 Bxe5 25. Bxh6 $40 {[%cal Gh4h5] White has attacking prospects.}) 24. Ra3 $1 {It is already difficult for Black.} c4 {is the engine's best move.} 25. Rf2 $36 {[%cal Gc1e3] All the pawns could be weak for Black. Not an easy position.} *

