{[%evp 0,21,18,27,27,5,34,16,27,7,15,15,7,7,24,16,33,33,17,16,20,28,18,15]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 e6 5. Bg2 Nbd7 6. O-O Bd6 {This is the only system we didn’t cover in 'Catalan Part 2,' and now is the perfect time to address it. In my opinion, it’s not a critical variation, but it has been played in over 2,500 games.} 7. Nfd2 $5 {[%cal Yd2c4,Gb1c3,Ge2e4] We defend the c4 pawn, and are ready to continue with Nc3-e4.} (7. Qc2 {good move in Catalan style, but my recommendation is much simpler.}) ({if we start with} 7. Nc3 {Black can consider} dxc4 {and things are not clear at all.}) 7... O-O 8. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] we are ready for e4, and Black's bishop on d6 is misplaced.} Re8 {Black's most common continuation.} (8... dxc4 $6 {cannot be good for Black.} 9. Nxc4 Bc7 10. b3 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3] Ba3 is in the air.}) (8... Bc7 {prophylactic move.} 9. e4 dxe4 {most common continuation.} (9... dxc4 10. e5 $1 Nd5 11. Nxc4 $16 {good positional advantage.}) 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 (10... h6 11. f4 $1 $16 {[%cal Re6e5] we stop e6-e5, and we can play for domination.}) 11. Nxe4 e5 {A very important move for Black; without it, Black risks being suffocated by White’s space advantage.} (11... f5 $2 12. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Gg5]}) 12. d5 cxd5 13. Bg5 $1 {much stronger than 13.cxd5.} ({after the natural} 13. cxd5 $6 {Black plays} h6 $1 $14 {[%cal Gc7b6] good move against Bg5. Black will continue with Bb6, and his position is only slightly worse, but very playable.}) 13... f6 14. Qxd5+ Kh8 15. Be3 $16 {very good advantage thanks to the much more active pieces.}) (8... Be7 {This move has been tried occasionally, but it acknowledges that the bishop on d6 was misplaced.} 9. e3 $5 $146 {we can just play useful moves and have a more pleasant position, for example:} (9. e4 {is not so strong now:} dxe4 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 f5 $1 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Ye7g5,Re4g5] compared to the 8...Bc7 variation, we don't have now Ng5.} 12. Nc3 e5 $11 {Black is doing fine.}) 9... b6 (9... Re8 10. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1] Rd1 next.}) 10. e4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc6] now e4 is stronger because Black's pawn on c6 is weak.}) (8... Bb4 {strange move, but it has also been tried.} 9. e4 $1 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 $14 {slightly better for us because of the pair of bishops.}) 9. e4 e5 $1 {only good option for Black, but it's extremely rare.} (9... dxe4 $6 {has been played in the 98% of the games that have reached this position, but it's bad:} 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Be7 12. Bf4 $16 {typical positional advantage for White.}) 10. dxe5 Nxe5 (10... Bxe5 $2 {wrong recapture.} 11. cxd5 $14 {just extra pawn without compensation for Black.}) 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 $1 (12. Nxd5 $6 {has been played in Roiz-Pasko, but it's a mistake:} Bg4 $1 $146 13. Qb3 Bc5 $36 {Black doesn't only have compensation, but also the initiative.}) 12... Bg4 $1 {only move for Black; otherwise we will play h3, and have a position with a full extra pawn.} 13. Qb3 Bf8 $1 $146 {Black's best continuation. It's a prophylactic move against Nde4.} (13... Bc5 $2 {was good against 12.Nxd5, but here it's a mistake because of} 14. Nde4 $16 {[%csl Rc5]}) (13... Rc8 $6 {Jirka-Doluhanova.} 14. Nde4 $1 Nf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bxf3 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Nb5 Qb6 18. Qxf3 Qxb5 19. d6 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4] Bf4 next, and Black has some problems.}) 14. Nc4 $5 {forces Black to find some other strong moves.} ({Black equalizes after the standard continuation} 14. h3 Bh5 15. Nde4 Nf3+ 16. Kh1 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Rxe4 18. Bxf3 Bxf3+ 19. Qxf3 Qxd5 20. Be3 Rae8 $11) 14... Nf3+ 15. Kh1 b5 $1 {I am not sure that everybody will find it, but it's Black's only way for full equality.} (15... Ne1 $2 {not immediately.} 16. Ne3 $1 $16) 16. Qxb5 (16. Nxb5 Rb8 $1 17. Bxf3 Rxb5 18. Qd3 Qd7 $1 $13 {Unclar, 0.00 for the engine, but could be interesting to check further.}) 16... Ne1 $3 17. Ne3 Bd7 $1 {we can see that 15...b5 was important because now Black wins an important tempo against our queen.} 18. Qa6 Nxg2 19. Nxg2 $44 {Black has full compensation for the pawn. CONCLUSIONS: This line is positionally dubious for Black. The only reasonable continuation is 9...e5, but it’s extremely rare. By move 14, White has numerous options, and it’s doubtful our opponents will enjoy such a position, where they must memorize countless engine lines in a completely new position—just to attempt a draw, with no guarantee of achieving it.} *

