{[%evp 0,41,61,30,20,0,25,33,37,16,13,19,16,-12,11,4,13,13,14,1,0,-18,-18,-20,-22,-1,-28,-13,-22,-22,4,-1,3,3,3,4,22,13,2,-12,-9,-26,-41,-25]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 {Black's critical moves are now Bf5 or b5.} Bf5 {This is Svilder's recommendation.} (8... b5 {This is a serious move and it was played by Carlsen, Dubov...} 9. Qc3 $5 {[%cal Gc3e1,Yf1d1,Yb1c3] This is my recommendation. The idea is to continue with Rd1-Qe1-Nc3-e4.} (9. Qb3 Be6 10. Qd1 {Dubov showed how to equalize with Black:} c5 $1 11. dxc5 Nc6 12. Nc3 b4 13. Nb5 Bd5 14. Nbd4 Qa5 $11 {Nakamura-Dubov, 2021.}) 9... Qb6 {This is Black's best, according to the engine.} (9... Bf5 10. Rd1 a5 {Now, we can use our main idea} 11. Qe1 $5 {[%cal Yb1c3,Ye2e4] Our idea is Nc3-e4. The e1 square could be the best place for our queen. Let's check two very high-level games: Svidler-Dubov and Ding-Aronian.} Bc2 {Dubov always knows engines' recommendations!} (11... Qc8 12. Nc3 Rd8 {Ding-Aronian, 2021.} 13. e4 $16 {White is much better.}) 12. Rd2 Bf5 {Black thinks that White's rook on d2 is misplaced.} 13. Nc3 (13. Ne5 $5 $146 {deserves attention.}) 13... Ne4 14. Rd1 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 b4 {Svidler played Qb3, but} 16. Qc5 $5 {deserves attention. Our idea is that after} Qd6 {we can play Qc4, or enter in an endgame:} 17. Qxd6 exd6 18. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1] Rac1 next, and White is definitely slightly better.}) 10. Rd1 $5 $146 (10. Ne5 {too early for this move.} Nd5 $1 11. Qd2 Nd7 {Black was ok in Svane-Abdusattorov, 2022.}) 10... Nbd7 (10... Bf5 11. Qe1 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ge2e4]}) 11. Qb3 $5 {[%cal Rc8e6] This looks interesting now because Black doesn't have anymore Be6. For example:} (11. Qe1 {is our standard move.}) 11... c5 12. Nc3 Rb8 13. Bf4 $14) (8... Be6 9. Qb4 $5 {more interesting for White.} ({if we play} 9. Qa4 {then Black can play} b5 10. Qc2 Bf5 {Black transposes to the 8...b5 variations but forced us to play Qc2 instead of our move Qc3.}) (9. Qc2 Bf5 10. Qd1) 9... Qb6 $1 {This concrete move is Black's strongest reaction.} (9... Qc7 10. Nc3 $14 {White is just slightly better.}) 10. Qxe7 Re8 11. Qa3 Na6 {Black plays for compensation.} 12. Nc3 {This is White's most interesting continuation, in my opinion.} Nb4 13. Qa4 (13. Na4 Qb5 14. Nc3 $11 {Is fine if you want to make a draw.}) 13... Bf5 {Now, we have a choice.} 14. Bd2 (14. a3 $5 {This is more ambitious.} Nc2 15. Ra2 Rad8 $1 {only move for Balck.} 16. e3 c5 $1 {Only move, and this already means that our opponent should be well prepared.} 17. d5 $5 {Interesting idea, because Black has to find many good moves to obtain an unclear position:} (17. e4 $5 Nxe4 18. g4 Be6 19. d5 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Bxd5 21. c4 Nb4 22. axb4 Bxc4 23. bxc5 Qe6 24. Ng5 Nxg5 25. Bxg5 Bxa2 $11 {Black reaches the equality, but he had to play very well for a lot of moves!}) 17... Bd3 $1 18. Nd2 $5 Nd4 $1 19. exd4 cxd4 20. Nd1 Rc8 $1 21. Ra1 Bh6 $1 $13 {Black has compensation.}) 14... Nbd5 15. e3 Qxb2 16. Rfc1 {We gave back the pawn, and we achieved a very playable position. For example:} Nxc3 17. Bxc3 Qb6 18. Be1 $14 {White is ready for a long and more pleasant game.}) 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {If we continue with standard moves, then it's not so easy to find ideas because Black has concrete measures against each of them.} 10. h3 $5 {[%cal Yg3g4] This is my recommendation. It's a useful move, and we wait for Black's next move. Sometimes, we may have the g3-g4 idea.} (10. Qb3 {This may look logical, but after} Qb6 11. Re1 Qxb3 $1 ({if Black plays not} 11... Ne4 {then we have an interesting position after because after} 12. Nh4 $14 {we have an interesting position.}) 12. axb3 {Normally this nedgame could be playable for us, but Black can play the concrete} Be6 $1 {[%csl Rb3] Attacking our pawn on b3.} 13. e4 {We can try to sacrifice the pawn.} (13. b4 {if we push the pawn, then after} a6 14. e4 Nb6 $11 {[%csl Rb2,Rb4,Yc4][%cal Yb6c4,Ye6c4] Looks nice, but difficult to improve our position, mainly because our queenside structure is not flexible, and Black has the c4 square.}) 13... Bxb3 $1 {but it's difficult to find something here, for example:} 14. Nd2 Be6 15. d5 cxd5 16. exd5 Bf5 17. Rxe7 Nc5 $11 {Black is absolutely fine.}) (10. Re1 {This is White's most common continuation, but I think Black equalizes with} Ne4 11. Qb3 Qa5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} ({not} 11... Qb6 {because after} 12. Nh4 $14 {we have an interesting position.}) 12. Bf4 Nb6 {[%cal Gf8d8] This position is very playable for Black. Next move could be Rfd8.} 13. Be5 $5 Bh6 $13 {not easy to find plans for White.}) 10... a5 {We now have two interesting continuations.} (10... Rc8 {Was tried by Tari, Sasikiran, Gupta, but after} 11. Qb3 Qb6 (11... Nb6 {I don't like this move for Black, after} 12. Rd1 Nfd5 13. Ng5 $1 Nxc3 14. bxc3 h6 15. Ne4 $14 {White had a nice pressure in Rodshtein-Tari, 2019.}) 12. Re1 Qxb3 (12... Ne4 13. g4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Be6 15. Qa3 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5] looks interesting for White. We can continue with Bg5.}) 13. axb3 {[%csl Ya7] Black's pawn on a7 is now hanging, and after} a6 14. e4 Be6 {we have} 15. Ng5 $1 Bxb3 16. Ra3 Bc4 17. b3 Bb5 18. e5 Nd5 19. Nxb5 axb5 20. e6 $16 {[%cal Ga3a7] And White has the advantage. Ra7 could be our next idea.}) (10... Ne4 {This is a logical move.} 11. Qb3 Qb6 (11... Nb6 $6 12. a4 $14 {[%csl Rb6] Knight on b6 is misplaced.}) 12. Rd1 Qxb3 13. axb3 Nb6 (13... Nxc3 $6 14. bxc3 Bc2 $2 15. Rd2 Bxb3 16. Rb2 $16) 14. Ne1 $5 Nd6 (14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Be6 16. Rb1 $14 {White was slightly better in Gelfand-Sutovsky, 2018.}) 15. e4 Be6 16. Ra3 $14 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ge1d3,Gd3c5] we protect our pawn, and we maintain control of the c4 square. Our next moves could be Be3-Nd3-Nc5.}) (10... Nb6 {doesn't have an independent value, because after} 11. Qb3 a5 $1 {we can decide if to play 12.g4 or 12.a4, and both moves will transpose in the 10...a5 variation.} (11... Ne4 $6 12. a4 a5 13. Rd1 $14 {Avrukh-Gupta, 2012.}) 12. a4 {transposes.} (12. g4 Be6 13. Qc2 {transposes.})) 11. g4 $5 $146 {This is