{[%evp 0,41,30,23,23,-16,38,22,35,4,10,2,2,2,4,7,39,7,-11,-2,5,-6,-7,-30,4,23,14,-1,29,21,7,32,32,31,-3,31,22,25,24,19,15,13,16,18]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. Qb3 a5 {This is Black's third most popular continuation.} 8. Rd1 {[%csl Yb3,Ye1][%cal Yb3e1] This is White's only interesting continuation, in my opinion. Sometimes, we will place our queen on the safe e1 square.} (8. cxd5 a4 9. Qd1 cxd5 10. Nc3 Ne4 $5 {Black is fine, and it's very difficult to get an interesting position for White.} (10... Qa5 $5)) 8... a4 9. Qb4 {Now, Black has different continuations.} dxc4 {Black's most common continuation.} (9... Qa5 10. Qxa5 Rxa5 11. Bd2 Ra8 12. Na3 $14 {We can play a long and slightly more pleasant endgame. For example:} Na6 13. Rac1 Bf5 14. Ne5 (14. cxd5 $5 {deserves attention.} cxd5 15. Nb5 {could be unpleasant for Black.}) 14... Rfc8 15. Be1 {White slowly improves his position.} Be6 {Dardha-Kadric, 2023.} 16. cxd5 $5 cxd5 17. Nb5 Ne4 18. Nc3 Nxc3 19. Bxc3 {Our pieces are better placed.}) (9... Ne4 $6 10. Nc3 $14 {White is already better.}) (9... Re8 {Has been played three times by Vachier Lagrave.} 10. Na3 Qd6 (10... e6 11. Bf4 Nbd7 12. Rac1 $14 {White is slightly better, for example:} Ne4 13. Ne5 $1 Bf8 14. Qe1 Nxe5 {Cheparinov-Ding, 2017.} 15. dxe5 $1 $16 {White already has a serious advantage.}) 11. Qe1 Qd8 {This was Vachier's idea, but I think we can find a way to play for White, for example:} 12. Bf4 $5 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1] Rac1 next, and White's position is for sure more pleasant.}) 10. Qxc4 Bf5 (10... Nbd7 $6 {A small mistake, in my opinion.} 11. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] we prepare e4.} Nb6 (11... Qa5 12. e4 e5 13. Bd2 Qa7 14. Bc3 $14) 12. e4 $14 {White has a good game.}) (10... Be6 11. Qb4 b5 {and now, we can play our main idea:} 12. Qe1 $5 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4] We are ready for e4, and it looks interesting for us.}) (10... b5 11. Qc5 $1 {[%cal Gf3e5] Only one game in this position. Our idea is Ne5.} (11. Qc2 $6 Bf5 $1 $15) 11... Bb7 {This is Black's most logical move, but now we can play} (11... Ne4 12. Qc2 Bf5 13. g4 $1 {Was played in the game Svane-Kochmar, 2022.} Nxf2 14. gxf5 Nxd1 15. Qxd1 c5 $1 16. Na3 $5 $14 {White's position is more interesting.}) 12. Qc2 {because Black doesn't have Bf5.} Na6 13. a3 $14 {Black still has some small problems.}) 11. e3 $5 {[%cal Gc4e2] our idea is Qe2.} Qd5 {This is probably Black's best idea.} (11... Qa5 12. Bd2 Qa6 13. Qxa6 Nxa6 14. Nc3 $14 {We have another more pleasant endgame.}) (11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 {[%cal Rc6c5] Not easy for Black to play c5.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black prepares e5.} (12... Qa5 13. Nc3 (13. h3 $5 Rfd8 14. g4 {playable for White.}) 13... Ne4 14. Nh4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Be6 16. Ba3) 13. Nc3 $1 e5 14. h3 $14 {Black's position is worse, for example:} Rfe8 (14... e4 15. Nd2 Rfe8 16. g4 Be6 17. Ndxe4 $16 {Black doesn't have enough compensation.}) 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nd4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rf5g4] Thanks to h3, Black doesn't have Bg4.}) 12. Qb4 $5 {[%cal Yb4e1] We are ready for our typical Qe1 idea.} (12. Qe2 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3] deserves attention. We want to play Nc3, but Black can play} Bxb1 $1 13. Rxb1 Qxa2 14. Qc2 $44 {We have compensation, but Black's position is objectively fine.}) 12... c5 $1 $146 {This is Black's strongest continuation, and it is a novelty.} (12... Bxb1 {Is not so good anymore, because after} 13. Rxb1 Qxa2 14. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gb4e7,Gb4b7] Black's e7 and b7 pawns are hanging.}) (12... Qd6 13. Qe1 {We want to continue with Nc3, and our position looks interesting. The engine finds} Bc2 $1 {and after} 14. Rd2 Bf5 $1 {back, but I guess we can try} 15. Nc3 Ne4 16. Rd1 $36 {Where our position has more potential.}) 13. Qa3 $5 {This is a more interesting direction. Black has many moves, but the critical line is} (13. Qxc5 Qxc5 14. dxc5 {Black should be in time to equalize:} Ne4 15. Nd4 Rd8 16. Nc3 Nxc5 17. Nxf5 Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 gxf5 19. Rb1 {We have two bishops, so we can try to play it, but Black should objectively be fine.}) 13... Rd8 14. Nc3 Qc4 (14... Qd6 15. Nh4 $5 Bc8 16. h3 cxd4 17. Rxd4 $36 {Looks interesting for White.}) 15. Ne5 Qb4 $1 {only move.} 16. Bd2 $5 Qxa3 17. bxa3 cxd4 18. exd4 {Black has to find the only move} Nc6 $1 {only move.} 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Nxc6 Rd7 21. Rac1 $44 {Black has enough compensation, but the game continues. CONCLUSIONS: 7...a5 is a very serious move, but it's still difficult for Black to kill the game. Maybe his best chance is to play 12...c5! which is a novelty, but also, after it, we still have some ideas. 7.Qb3 is a safe option, and you can play it if you are fine with playing a more pleasant game without any risk. If you want to play more ambitiously, then you can opt for 7.Nc3, which we have analyzed in chapters 10-11-12. Thank you!} *

