{[%evp 0,21,30,29,24,-10,24,26,40,6,-5,10,8,8,5,12,3,-5,-6,0,3,4,10,6]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 b5 (5... g6 {transposes to Unit 3.}) (5... Nbd7 6. O-O e6 7. a4 $1 {[%cal Rb7b5] We stop b7-b5 ideas.} (7. Nbd2 b5 $132) 7... a5 {Most common continuation.} (7... b6 {has been tried in some high-level games.} 8. Nfd2 {if we take on c4, our position is just better, but we must check the critical move} Ba6 9. Bxc6 {necessary.} Rc8 10. Bb5 $1 {Very important move to remember. We'll study this variation in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) 8. Qc2 b5 {Critical continuation.} (8... Nb6 9. Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gd2c4] Nxc4 next, and it's just positionally better for White.}) 9. Ne5 {White's big main line, you can play it because it's risk-free, but if Black knows a lot of concrete moves, then it will be a draw. We'll study it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 6. Ne5 Bb7 7. O-O e6 8. b3 {I prefer this move, because in the concrete lines, like the game Donchenko-Pechac, theory might change, but we try to build a repertoire for your whole life.} (8. Nc3 {GM Dubov plays this often. We usually follow him, because he is an expert in the Catalan.} a6 9. b3 b4 $1 {is a very strong move in this move order.} (9... cxb3 {We have this position in our database, so we are fine here.}) 10. Ne4 Nxe4 {Black should take first.} (10... c3 $2 {Both GM Shirov and Le played this automatic mistake.} 11. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Rf7]}) 11. Bxe4 c3 12. a3 a5 13. axb4 Bxb4 $13 {I tried to analyze this position, but it is quite good for Black.}) (8. a4 {Main line, but I don't believe too much in this move.} a6 9. b3 {I don't think that is a good inclusion for White.} cxb3 10. Qxb3 Qxd4 {A lot of the games follow this critical line.} 11. Bb2 Qb4 {If Black knows well the theory, it is not easy to win.} 12. Qc2 Qc5 13. Qd3 Be7 14. Nd2 Qb6 $1 {Very important move.} 15. Ne4 {We can check the game Donchenko-Pechac.} Nd5 16. h4 $5 (16. Nxf7 {White tried many times, but it is a proven draw in the end.}) 16... c5 17. Ng5 {Very concrete variation.} c4 18. Qc2 (18. Qb1 $6 {allows} c3 $36) 18... Nb4 19. Qb1 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 f6 {The young players are very well prepared, I am not sure that this was only the start of their analysis.} 21. Nef3 {Donchenko played the best move.} Nd7 $11 {They played quite well for the few next moves and the game ended in a draw.}) 8... cxb3 9. axb3 $5 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gd1d4] We aim for a long game playing for the compensation. It is not interesting to just follow a game, see if our opponent remembers.} (9. Qxb3 {is possible, but Black can equalize, another game was played here by GM Pechac, leading expert in this line for Black. He knows the best moves.} Qxd4 10. Bf4 {This was the game Petrov-Pechac, and Black of course knew everything.} Nd5 11. Rd1 Qa4 12. Qd3 Be7 13. Nc3 Qa6 $1 {By far the best move.} 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. e4 d4 {Pechac played a move that is +0.10 initially, but just empty.} (15... f6 {I started to analyze this, where maybe} 16. Ng6 $5 {is interesting.} hxg6 17. exd5 $13 {0.00, but new position.}) 16. Rab1 {can be tried maybe, but I am sure that Pechac knew everything also here.} (16. Qb3 $6 {was the move played in the game.} O-O $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) 16... b4 $1 17. Qxd4 O-O 18. Bf1 {We have for sure compensation, but soon it will be an equal endgame.} Qb6 {Qxa2 is also possible.} 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. Nd7 Bxe4 21. Nxf8 {White has two bishops, but it is very concrete.} Bxb1 22. Rxb1 Bxf8 23. Bg2 Rxa2 24. Bxb8 Bc5 {Black has some kind of fortress, especially if they manage to win the f2 pawn.} 25. Rf1 b3 26. Be4 $11 {It is draw with many moves.}) 9... Be7 {The most common move.} (9... Nbd7 $6 {was played by Dreev against Carlsen in a rapid game, but it is not great because of} 10. Nxc6 Qb6 11. d5 $1 {Strong move played by Carlsen.} Nxd5 12. Na5 $16 {White got a big advantage.}) (9... Nfd7 {[%csl Rb8,Rd7] was also tried with the idea to exchange knights, but protect c6. The knights are not great though.} 10. Nd3 $16 {I like this move played by Dubov against Narayanan. This is all you need to remember, White is better.} Be7 11. Nc3 {It is a very instructive game, we can always learn how to play this structure from GM Dubov.} b4 12. Ne4 O-O 13. Bf4 a5 14. Qc2 {Normal development so far.} Na6 15. Rfd1 Nc7 16. Nec5 {Very good move.} Nxc5 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5 Qc8 {And now a very important moment.} 19. Bxc7 $1 {We take the knight and play for domination.} (19. Bd6 {was played in the game.} Re8 20. Bh3 {[%cal Gc7d5,Gc7b5] But after both Nd5 or Nb5, Black is fine.} Nb5 $13 {Dubov won in the end, but it was a blitz game.}) 19... Qxc7 20. Rd6 $16 {[%csl Rb7] Black is much worse here.}) 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] Black has different moves here.} a6 {The most played move, We'll consider it in "Position 4" of this Unit.} (10... O-O {was played by Tomashevsky against Eljanov in 2015. We'll consider it in Position 3 of this Unit, together with some other moves like:}) (10... Qb6 {Second most played option.}) (10... Nd5 {is not a great move, because it gives the important e4 squares to our knight.}) 11. Bb2 {Normal move, in these positions, we always have compensation, which is good news. We don't need to rush to regain material, we can play for squares, for activity and for interesting ideas.} *

