{[%evp 0,33,17,21,18,-2,45,18,25,3,3,4,24,5,4,-10,-1,-3,0,-7,8,-18,25,18,40,39,32,43,51,34,48,33,71,21,50,46]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 b5 6. Ne5 Bb7 7. O-O e6 8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3 Be7 10. Nc3 a6 {The most played move. This position can also arise from the Catlan move order.} 11. Bb2 {Normal move, in these positions, we always have compensation, which is good news. We don't need to rush to regain material, we can play for squares, for activity and for interesting ideas.} O-O (11... Nbd7 $2 {is not good here, because of} 12. Nxc6 $16 {The king is still in the center.}) 12. Ne4 {This is the starting position of our line.} (12. Qc2 {is not good, because Black can play now} Nbd7 {And the queen is misplaced.} 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc8c2]}) 12... Nxe4 {is the best move for Black.} (12... Nbd7 $2 {is a big mistake.} 13. Nxc6 $1 {We regain the pawn on our terms.} Qe8 14. Nd2 {Domination.} Bd6 15. Ne7+ Qxe7 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. Bc6 $16 {White is obviously better here.}) (12... Nd5 {was played in the game Salem-Niemann, 2021.} 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. dxc5 f6 15. Nd3 {looks interesting, but in reality, Black here has only one good move.} a5 $1 {is the only way to hold the position.} (15... Nd7 $2 {Niemann played natural move, but after} 16. e4 Nc7 17. Bc3 {Very big domination, very big advantage. We can see how it went.} Qe7 18. Ba5 {[%csl Ga5,Rc7] The bishop is fantastic on a5.} Rac8 19. f4 e5 20. f5 {Simply domination.} Rfd8 21. Qc2 {Now Niemann played some panic decisions.} g6 22. fxg6 hxg6 23. Bh3 {The bishop on h3 is now very strong.} Rf8 24. Rad1 Ne6 25. Bxe6+ {No counterplay allowed, and it was game over pretty soon.} Qxe6 26. Nf2 Rce8 27. Rd6 Qf7 28. Ng4 $18 {Black can resign.}) 16. e4 Nc7 17. Qc2 b4 {[%cal Gb7a6] This is Black's point behind a5, the bishop can sometimes be activated.} 18. Rfc1 $146 {Maybe the rook can protect c5 and it will be necessary at some point.} (18. Rfd1 {was played in the game, Wang-Nagy, but maybe our rook can be slightly more useful on c1.} Qe7 19. e5 {Players agreed to a draw.} f5 $13 {Still complicated, but playable for both sides.}) (18. e5 f5 19. Nf4 Qe7 20. Rfc1) 18... Qe7 {If Black plays in the same way:} 19. e5 f5 20. Ne1 $14 {[%cal Ge1f3,Gf3d4] We can reroute the knight to d4, slow game, but White has chances. +0.15.}) (12... Qb6 {is not a good move, we can play for the squares after} 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd3 {Two pawns sacrificed, but two bishops and dark squares.} Qb6 {Now White can play for an attack.} (15... Qe7 16. Ba3 $16) 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Qd2 $40 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gd3f4,Gf4h5] The king is very vulnerable.}) (12... Nfd7 13. Qc2 Qb6 {was played in a very nice game Kramnik-Giri, Qatar Masters 2014.} (13... Nxe5 $6 14. dxe5 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ge4d6,Gf1d1] We have the fantastic squar for the knight.}) 14. Nd3 a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4] is very good move, not easy to find something more useful.} (14... Rc8 {We can just play} 15. Nec5 $14 {Difficult to find moves for Black.}) 15. Ndc5 {[%csl Rb8,Rd7] Black's knights look a bit strange.} (15. Nec5 $5 {Matter of taste.}) 15... Bc8 16. Qc3 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc3g7] Typical move, to throw an eye on the g7 pawn.} (16. Rfc1 $36 {Other useful moves also exist.}) (16. h4 $36 {also useful.}) 16... b4 {[%csl Yb2,Yc3,Rg7] Best move, Black is not comfortable with the strong battery eyeing the king.} 17. Qe3 Na6 (17... Qc7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] was maybe the best plan, to reroute the knight.}) 18. Rfc1 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5] Giri transfers the knight to d5.} 19. Nxd7 Bxd7 20. Nc5 Be8 {Necessary.} 21. Ra2 {[%cal Gc1a1] Not only move, but useful, maybe one day a5 pawn can be weak. White has fantastic pieces.} Qb5 22. Qd3 $5 {Quite an interesting decision.} Qxd3 {Black had better moves, but Giri thought that the endgame should be safe enough.} 23. Nxd3 Nd5 {Pawn up for Black, what can go wrong? Maximum draw?} 24. Ne5 {No, look how Kramnik increases the pressure.} Ra6 25. Bf1 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gf1a6] Eyeing the rook, already not easy to understand what to do, e4 is a threat.} Nc3 {Giri thought that if he is meant to give back one pawn, at least win the pair of bishops.} 26. Bxc3 bxc3 27. Rxc3 {[%csl Ra5,Rc6,Rf8] But all of the pawns are weak, no development.} c5 $2 {Here comes the panic move c5, and after} 28. dxc5 Bf6 29. f4 $18 {White's position is completely winning, and Kramnik won convincingly.}) 13. Bxe4 {Now again a lot of moves, but we check them for understanding, it is not important to remember move by move, but the ideas.} a5 {The best move, in my opinion.} (13... Ra7 $2 {was played in the game Moiseenko-Postny, but it is a bad move.} 14. Qc2 h6 15. Qc3 {White used Kramnik's idea.} Bf6 16. Ba3 $146 {was stronger, with big advantage.} Re8 17. Qc5 {Some immediate tactical shot ends the game after} Ra8 18. Nxf7 $1 {Attack is too strong.} Kxf7 19. Qh5+ Kg8 20. Qg6 $18) (13... f6 $2 {[%csl Re6,Rf6] was played in Dubov-Le, but it is always a bad sign, because the e6 pawn becomes a target.} 14. Nd3 Bd6 15. Qc2 Nd7 {Dubov won, it was a blitz game, now} 16. Nc5 $18 {was crushing, huge advantage, maybe even winning.}) (13... Qb6 $6 {is also not a great move.} 14. Qc2 {White has a very good position.} g6 $2 {was played in the game Rakhmanov-Pershin, but now White has a huge attack.} (14... h6 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge5d3,Gd3c5] was needed, but White can play for domination.}) 15. h4 f6 16. Bxg6 $18 {White had a winning attack and won.}) 14. Qc2 {I prefer the more classical square for the queen.} (14. Qd3 $5 {Also possible.}) 14... h6 (14... f5 $2 {[%csl Rf5] is a mistake and a very weakening move.} 15. Bg2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] In the future, we may have e4 ideas.}) 15. Rfd1 {I prefer this move more.} (15. Rfc1 {was played in the game Dubov-Anton Guijarro.} Bf6 16. Qc3 $146 {Comparing to the main line, Black has} Bxe5 $5 17. dxe5 $13 {[%csl Yc1] The rook is worse on c1 than on d1.}) 15... Bf6 16. Qc3 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge5c6] Black needs to play a careful move, but it is not easy.} (16. Ng4 {No need to rush.}) 16... Ra6 {defends everything, but is very passive.} 17. Bc2 $40 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gc3d3,Gd3h7] We have a clear plan to play for mate. Very interesting position. I don't want to say that White has an objective advantage, but at the very least we get what we want - a game! If you compare this final position, with the one after 8.a4, you see what I mean. There are no concrete lines, forced complications, where Black remembers everything and equalizes, it is only a position where White has long term compensation and easy to play. That's why I believe that practically speaking, playing for compensation after axb3 is a very interesting weapon that we can use in practice for a long period of time.} *

