{[%evp 0,23,24,13,19,-11,-4,-11,6,-11,14,2,-13,3,14,12,14,14,6,-12,0,-1,18,13,17,22]} 1. d4 Nf6 ({This Unit will be interesting for us in the following move order:} 1... d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 e6 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2) 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 {[%csl Yd2][%cal Ge2e4] Against the Nbd7 move order, Nbd2 is a very simple and straight-forward way. Our idea is to prepare e2-e4.} b6 (8... Re8 $6 {[%csl Rc8] This is a slow and harmless move. Black's priority is to solve the Bc8 problem, that's why 8...Re8 is not a good way.} 9. e4 $1 {We play the typical idea of the position.} dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 {[%csl Rc8] And Black's position is much worse because of the Bc8 problem.} Nf6 {Black's most common continuation, and this position was reached more than 400 times, but after} (11... e5 $1 {Is the best, according to the engine, but it shows how bad Black's position is.} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bc5 14. Be3 Qb6 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Re5] Black can try to hold, but we have an extra pawn, and the situation is obviously very good for us. If this is Black's best position, then it means that 8...Re8 is not a good move.}) (11... Bf6 {[%cal Ye6e5] Black prepares e5, but he will never be in time to play it:} 12. Re1 e5 13. Bf4 $1 $16) 12. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Re6e5,Yc6c5,Yf1d1,Gb7b6,Gf3e5] White's position is much better. Black has the Bc8 problem, he can never play b6, he can never play e5, and in case of c5, we can play Rd1 with a huge advantage.}) (8... c5 {This move has some sense, but why did Black not play it at move 7, then?} 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. b4 $5 Nce4 {necessary move.} (10... Ncd7 11. a3 $14 {Just better for White.}) 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 (11... dxe4 $2 12. Rd1 $16 {[%csl Rd8]}) 12. Rb1 {Black's position is not lost, but it's passive. For example:} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] best move.} 13. Rd1 Bb7 14. Nd4 {[%cal Gg2e4] Bxe4 is already a threat.} Qc8 (14... Qc7 $2 15. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) 15. Be3 $14) (8... dxc4 $2 {In this concrete position, dxc4 is a very bad move, after} 9. Nxc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc8] We have a fantastic position, and Black still has the Bc8 problem.} b6 $2 {Is never possible because of} 10. Nfe5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc6]}) 9. e4 Bb7 (9... Ba6 {This move is possible, but it's very rare, and it doesn't have a clear logic. If Black wants to play with Ba6, then it's much better for him to start with 7...b6 and Ba6 immediately.} 10. e5 Ne8 11. Re1 {We will see it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) (9... dxe4 {This move was played in more than 2000 games. It's a move with a lot of historical games, but nowadays, it's clear that this is not the best way for Black.} 10. Nxe4 {[%csl Rc8] Black generally has the problem of his Bc8. We'll discuss it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (9... dxc4 {This move is very important, but it will be even more important in another lesson, with a slightly different position.} 10. Nxc4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is ready for c6-c5. We'll discuss it in "Position 5" of this Unit.}) 10. e5 ({Be careful to don't start with} 10. cxd5 cxd5 {because after} 11. e5 {Black can play} Ne4 $1 {(also 11...Rc8 and then Ne4 is fine for him)}) 10... Ne8 11. cxd5 {This position was important for the Catalan many years ago.} exd5 {This is probably the best recapture, but also the less common one.} (11... cxd5 {was played in 1000 games. White's position is better, but it's useful to know the typical ideas.} 12. Re1 $1 {[%csl Yf1][%cal Yg2f1,Yd2f1] White's best move. Re1 is very useful against Ba6 ideas, but it also frees the f1 square for the knight or for the bishop. We'll discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 12. Re1 {[%csl Ge6,Yf5][%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Yd2f1,Yf1e3,Ye3f5] Black usually transfers his knight on e6, and we transfer our one to f5. We'll discuss it in "Position 4" of this Unit.} *

