{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,-11,0,0,-14,14,14,-2,-3,26,16,8,13,11,14,5,5,43,-13,23,15,14,-2,8,-9,10,19,13,4,22,5,26,-13,40,-31,10,6,6,6,24,-4]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 Bb7 10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 {was played in 1000 games. White's position is better, but it's useful to know the typical ideas.} 12. Re1 $1 {[%csl Yf1][%cal Yg2f1,Yd2f1] White's best move. Re1 is very useful against Ba6 ideas, but it also frees the f1 square for the knight or for the bishop.} Rc8 (12... Qc7 13. Qd1 {We need to keep the queens because we will play for the kingside attack.} (13. Qxc7 $6 {Very important rule: don't exchange queens in this structure!} Nxc7 $11 {Black's position is absolutely fine.}) 13... Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c2]} 14. Nb1 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3] very important move.} b5 (14... Qc2 $2 15. Qxc2 Rxc2 16. Nc3 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gg2f1,Gf1d3] Black has huge problems with the rook.} Bb4 17. Re3 $18) (14... Ba6 15. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Rc7c2] Our knight blocks Qc2 ideas.}) 15. a3 $1 a5 16. Bf1 b4 17. axb4 axb4 18. Nbd2 Qc2 {now the structure has changed, and we can go for a much better endgame:} 19. Qxc2 Rxc2 20. Nb3 $18 {[%csl Ga1,Gb3,Rb4]}) 13. Qd1 $1 {[%csl Gd1] Our queen is very good on d1. Eventually, it will join the kingside attack in the future.} (13. Qa4 {Is White's most common move, but queen on a4 is not fantastic, and Black can play} a5 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb7a6] Ba6 next. Still the position is better for White, because the structure is good for us, but the queen on a4 is not fantastic.}) 13... Ba6 {Normal move to take control of the diagonal, but we play standard ideas:} (13... Qc7 14. Nb1 $1 {Transposes to 12...Qc7.}) 14. Nf1 Nb8 15. h4 Nc6 16. a3 Na5 17. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gf1h2] We have very big attacking chances, and our position is seriously better.} *

