{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,-11,0,0,-14,14,14,-2,-3,26,16,8,13,11,14,5,5,43,-13,23,15,14,-2,8,-9,10,19,13,4,22,5,26,-13,40,-31,10,6,6,6,24,-4]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 Bb7 10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 exd5 {This is probably the best recapture, but also the less common one.} 12. Re1 Nc7 {Black's best plan is to transfer the knight on e6.} 13. Nf1 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf1e3,Ge3f5]} Ne6 14. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3f5]} c5 (14... Re8 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. h4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg8] Very big chances for an attack.}) (14... g6 {Stops Nf5, but weakens a lot of squares:} 15. b3 Rc8 16. Bb2 c5 17. Qd2 $16) 15. Nf5 Re8 (15... Rc8 16. Qd1 {[%csl Gd1] our queen is good on d1.} Re8 {trans to 15...Re8.}) (15... c4 $2 {very big positional mistake, after} 16. h4 $18 {Our position is winning, because we can just continue the attack.}) 16. Qd1 {[%csl Gd1] Our queen is very good on d1.} Bf8 (16... Rc8 17. b4 $5 Bf8 $1 {Black's best, according to the engine, and we transpose in 16...Bf8.}) 17. b4 $5 {I like a lot this positional idea.} (17. h4 $5 {also possible.}) 17... Rc8 (17... cxb4 {[%csl Gd4] Black wins a pawn, but our center is very solid, and we can just continue the attack} 18. h4 $16) (17... cxd4 18. N3xd4 Nxd4 19. Qxd4 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c4]} 20. Bd2 Rc4 21. Qb2 Qb8 {looks critical, but we are better after} 22. Nd6 $1 Bxd6 23. exd6 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Qxd6 25. Re8+ Nf8 26. b5 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gd2b4] Two bishops and much better pieces. Our plan could be a3-Bb4.}) 18. a3 {We support our pawn on b4. THe position is new, but we can check a bit further to understand the ideas:} a5 $1 {Black creates maximum pressure.} (18... cxd4 19. Bb2 $1 $16) (18... cxb4 $2 {Positional mistake.} 19. axb4 Bxb4 20. Bd2 $18 {[%csl Ra7,Gd4]}) 19. Bh3 $1 {We improve our bishop.} Bc6 (19... cxb4 20. axb4 Bxb4 21. Re3 $5 $14 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gc1a3] Ba3 next, we will exchange the bishops and play against Black's king.}) 20. Rb1 axb4 21. axb4 Ra8 22. Bd2 $14 {Pressure, pressure and pressure.} *

