{[%evp 0,22,21,21,29,19,22,15,15,-5,6,5,18,17,26,14,14,14,14,-13,-15,-3,23,33,22]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 b6 8. Rd1 Ba6 {[%cal Rc6c5] Ba6 looks active, but it will be more difficult for Black to execute the typical c6-c5.} 9. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Rb8d7] We stop Black's classical Nbd7 development.} Qc8 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb8d7,Yc8c6] Black protects the c6 pawn and is ready for Nbd7.} (9... Nfd7 {Important move, and now we need to act energetically:} 10. cxd5 cxd5 (10... Nxe5 $2 {is bad only because of the typical tactical idea} 11. d6 $1 Qxd6 12. Bf4 $16) 11. e4 $1 {[%csl Ra6] Very important move. We make profit of Black's misplaced bishop on a6, which doesn't control the key e4 square.} Nxe5 (11... Nf6 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Yg5f6] We fight for the e4 and d5 squares.} Nxe4 14. Nxe4 f6 $1 {Erigaisi-Khegay, 2019.} (14... dxe4 $4 15. Bxe4 $18) 15. Nc3 $1 $146 fxe5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Re1 $14 {We have a positional advantage.}) 12. exd5 $1 {Very important move.} Nd3 13. d6 Qxd6 14. Bxa8 Nb4 $1 (14... Qxd4 $2 15. Nc3 $18 {Raczek-Moussard, 2024.}) 15. Qa4 Be2 $1 $146 {Only move for Black. It leads to a new very interesting position.} (15... b5 $2 16. Qb3 N8c6 17. Bf4 Qd7 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 19. Rc1 $16 {Black did not have compensation for the missing exchange in the game Kociscak-Sahidi, 2021.}) 16. Rd2 b5 $1 17. Qb3 {The difference with the Sahidi's game, is that now Black's bishop can go on c4.} Bc4 $1 (17... N8c6 $2 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 19. Nc3 Bg4 20. d5 $1 $16) 18. Qd1 Bg5 $1 {Black provokes f2-f4, which weakens our king.} 19. f4 Bf6 20. Bg2 N8c6 21. Nc3 Bxd4+ 22. Kh1 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ya2a3] Black has some compensation, but probably not the full one. Still, this is a very interesting position, that deserves a try from Black's players.}) 10. Bf4 {We place our bishop on the most active position. Black's position is not so bad; the only question is whether he will be in time to complete the development. That's why the game often gets concrete.} Nh5 (10... Nbd7 11. cxd5 cxd5 (11... Nxe5 $2 {bad move, but only for one reason:} 12. d6 $1 $16 {As was played in the game Razuvaev-Borgo, 2000.}) 12. Nc3 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ga1c1] Our idea is to take control of the 'c' file.} Nh5 {Black's idea is to force our bishop to leave the strong h2-b8 diagonal.} (12... Qb7 $6 {Not a good move because of} 13. e4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gg2b7]}) 13. Be3 Nhf6 (13... Nxe5 $2 14. dxe5 $16 {[%csl Rh5] Black has problems with the knight on h5.}) 14. Qa4 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Ga1c1] We can play Rac1, and then b4-b5 idea.}) 11. cxd5 cxd5 {was played in the game Skebris-Tiviakov, 2009. Now, White's only chance to fight for the advantage is} 12. Qxc8 $1 $146 Rxc8 13. e4 $1 {Without this idea, Black's position would be absolutely fine.} f6 $1 {only move, otherwise our position is seriously better.} 14. exd5 $1 {We go for complications because we have to. Once again, if we don't play concrete, Black's position will be fine.} fxe5 $1 {necessary.} (14... Bb7 $2 {Important line for the evaluation of the position:} 15. Nd3 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Bxb8 Raxb8 18. g4 $18 {[%csl Rh5] Black lost his knight.}) (14... Nxf4 15. gxf4 Bb7 16. Ng4 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg4e3] Black will lose the d5 pawn.}) 15. Bxe5 Bb7 16. dxe6 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Nc6 18. Nc3 $14 {We have three pawns for Black's piece, and it seems that it's not so easy for Black to equalize.} *

