{[%evp 0,37,31,10,10,6,10,10,13,-20,9,-1,5,5,24,13,15,4,-1,-3,4,4,43,39,39,45,36,38,48,54,50,22,83,55,40,60,41,44,89,50]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 b6 8. Rd1 Bb7 (8... Nbd7 {The main position can arise also from this move order.} 9. b3 Bb7 10. Nc3 {And we transpose.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Yb7] We can commit the knight to c3 already, be careful because against 8...Nbd7 we cannot play the same move.} Nbd7 {Black's most common and best move.} (9... Na6 {is not a good square for the knight.} 10. a3 {[%csl Ra6] We limit the knight.} Qc8 {was played by Morozevich.} (10... dxc4 {In case of capture, we can go for the same.} 11. Ne5 Qc8 12. Bg5 {We play this move again.} c5 13. Ne4 {Probably Black's best is to simplify.} Bxe4 (13... Nxe4 {leads to the same.} 14. Bxe7) 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe7 Re8 16. Qxe4 Rxe7 17. Nxc4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Gc6] But of course, the position is not equal. In all of these positions, to have the c6 square is a huge advantage.}) 11. e4 {We can push e4 already.} Nxe4 {is how the game continued.} (11... dxc4 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 {[%csl Ra6] Once again, Black's knight on a6 is misplaced.} h6 14. g4 $40 {[%cal Gg4g5] Big attack.}) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 c5 14. d5 {is a strong move.} Re8 15. Qc2 $16 {Always Black's knight is misplaced, and Whtie won a nice game in Piket-Morozevich, 1996.}) (9... dxc4 {is not great.} 10. Ne5 Qc8 {Black is ready to play c5.} 11. Bg5 {We can play this move for now.} (11. Nxc4 $6 {is not a good idea.} c5 $11 {Black is absolutely fine.}) 11... c5 12. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gg5] That's the point behind Bg5.} Nc6 (12... cxd4 $2 {is already very bad.} 13. Rxd4 $16) 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. dxc5 {We can take here first, to force bxc5.} bxc5 15. Nxf6+ {Now Black's structure is ruined.} Bxf6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. Qxc4 $14 {White has the better structure, 2 results position.}) 10. b3 {This is the main position of the line. Black has different moves: Rc8 is by far the most common one, but other moves exist and all are better than Rc8.} Rc8 {The most common and the worst one between Black's logical options, in my opinion.} (10... c5 {Better than Rc8, but we can play a positional game after} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 {is probably more precise.} (11... exd5 {We don't need to analyze the position, just very nice game.} 12. dxc5 {is even stronger.} (12. Bb2 $5 {is possible and just play.}) 12... Bxc5 {Probably best.} (12... bxc5 13. Nh4 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh4f5] Typical idea, problems with the pawn, Nf5 is coming.}) 13. Bb2 Rc8 14. Qf5 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1] Isolated pawn, very good position for White.}) 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 {is critical, but we can push e4 now.} (12... exd5 {is once again just a good position for White.} 13. Bb2 {Slightly better simply.} Rc8 14. dxc5 {Maybe we can take.} bxc5 (14... Nxc5 15. Qf5 $14) 15. Ne1 {[%csl Rd5] Typical idea, to improve both the knight and the bishop.} Nf6 16. Rac1 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3,Ge1d3,Gd3f4] Slow game, good position.}) 13. e4 Bb7 14. dxc5 {Safe option, to play for small advantage.} (14. d5 $5 {More ambitious.} exd5 15. exd5 Bf6 16. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Rb7] The bishop on b7 is passive.}) 14... Rc8 15. Qe2 $14 {Typically slightly better for White.}) (10... Ba6 {is not a bad move, but it's quite dangerous from a practical point of view, White has many possible ideas, I will show you one, I liked it a lot.} 11. e4 $5 {My offer.} (11. Bb2 {There are more games here, but can be also interesting.} dxc4 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4 {White as usual plays for compensation.} b5 {is the best move, but b5 is b5.} (14... cxb3 $2 {looks quite bad already.} 15. axb3 Bb7 16. Nd6 $16) 15. Bd4 $44 {[%csl Yc5] White can at least play for the c5 square.}) 11... dxc4 {Black's idea.} 12. Bf4 {I believe it is even more interesting. Let's see some examples played in high-level games.} (12. e5 $5 {possible move.} Nd5 13. bxc4 Bxc4 14. Ne4 {Black has an extra pawn, but some problems.} b5 {Only move.} 15. Neg5 g6 16. Ne4 $44 {For sure compensation, I don't know about advantage.}) 12... h6 {was played in the game Kourkoulos-Bernadskiy, 2022. It's a normal move against Ng5. White took 13.bxc4 which is not great, but we can continue with} (12... b5 $2 {was played in the game Cheparinov-Gelfand, but it is a mistake. I think it was a blitz game, because usually Gelfand doesn't commit such mistakes in classical.} 13. bxc4 bxc4 {[%csl Yc4,Yc6] This is compensation by itself, because the structure is now terrible for Black.} 14. Rab1 $5 {Cheparinov played another move, but this is good.} Qa5 15. d5 {We can already play concrete.} cxd5 16. exd5 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gd4c6] A knight is coming to c6.} Rac8 $1 {Maybe Black can survive somehow with only moves.} 17. Nd4 exd5 18. Nxd5 $5 {Also possible.} (18. Nf5 $36 {Difficult to play for Black, maybe so move by move engine magic.}) 18... Nxd5 19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. Nf5 {How to play with Black good question?} Qc5 21. Rd5 $1 Qa3 $2 22. Bc1 $18) (12... cxb3 13. axb3 Bb7 {was played in the game Adly-Idani.} 14. e5 $146 {is better than the timid 14.h3 played in the game.} Nd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Bf1 $1 {is an important move, to activate our bishop, because not only we do that, but we also play against Black's b7 bishop.} a5 {Black is not in time.} 17. Bd3 {[%csl Rh7] Tempo, provoke a weakness.} g6 (17... h6 {is also a weakness.} 18. Qe2 $40 {[%csl Ra6,Yh6][%cal Gh2h4,Gg1g2] Sometimes some sacrifice might be possible on h6, very difficult to play for Black.}) 18. Qe2 $40 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] Stops Ba6, easy play next.}) (12... Qc8 {was played in the game Ragger-Grigoriants, White continued with 13.h4, which is a great move, but we can also use the same idea.} 13. Nd2 $5 {We force cxb3 transformation.} cxb3 14. axb3 Bb7 15. Nc4 $36 {And a lot of initiative.}) 13. Nd2 $146 {We now threaten to take so Black's reply is forced.} cxb3 14. axb3 {[%csl Ra6] Our rook comes into play.} Bb7 15. Nc4 $36 {Fantastic compensation, we can speak about initiative also, very difficult to play for Black.}) (10... Qc8 {was played in the game Postny-Narayanan, 2024. Postny is an expert in the Catalan, while Narayanan is an expert in any opening.} 11. a4 $5 {I want to offer you this move. What is the idea?} (11. Bb2 {is how it continued, and Black tried to argue that after} Ba6 $13 {[%csl Gb2,Rc8] Maybe the inclusion of Bb2 and Qc8 is good for Black. It is still playable and not clear.}) 11... Ba6 {[%cal Gc1a3] is normal, but now we have an extra option.} (11... c5 {We can play in the same way as 10...c5.} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bb2 $14 {[%csl Ga4,Rc8] The inclusion of this moves doesn't change the evaluation, usually Black's rook belong on c8.}) 12. Ba3 {This is the idea of why we played a4. We exchange the bishops. For example:} (12. e4 $5 {can also be considered, why not?} dxc4 13. bxc4 Bxc4 14. e5 Nd5 15. Ne4 {can also be very interesting, fantastic compensation.} Qa6 16. Ba3 $36 {[%csl Gd6,Gg5] The dark squares, it looks quite bad for Black.}) 12... Bxa3 13. Rxa3 dxc4 {Critical.} 14. bxc4 Bxc4 15. Ne5 {We can play this now.} Nxe5 16. dxe5 {[%csl Yd6] White will have fantastic compensation thanks to the d6 square.} Nd5 17. Ne4 $36 {[%cal Ge4d6] I like a lot this plan of a4-Ba3.}) 11. e4 Nxe4 {Black's most precise way to capture on e4.} (11... c5 {If Black plays logically, our reaction is} 12. exd5 exd5 13. Bb2 {White's position is just better, important concept to remember is that once Black takes on c4:} dxc4 {is met with} (13... cxd4 $5 14. Nxd4 $16 {dxc4 is impossible now because of the bishop.}) 14. d5 $1 {Very important positional idea. d6 is a threat.} (14. bxc4 $6 {Black would be happy to see this move, as it allows Black to take on d4.} cxd4 15. Rxd4 {Still it is small advantage for White, but White has to play very concrete} Bc5 16. Rf4 $13 {Nobody knows where this position could end.}) 14... Ne8 (14... cxb3 $6 15. axb3 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gd5d6,Ga1a7] We are in time to play} Ne8 16. Rxa7 $16 {[%csl Ra7] We gain back the pawn.}) 15. bxc4 Nd6 16. Nd2 $16 {White has a big positional advantage.}) (11... dxe4 {is more common, but less precise, first of all we can transpose to 11...Nxe4, but} 12. Ng5 $5 {White has this extra option, which also might be very good.}) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 {We have something similar in the previous Unit. Black has tried some moves, but the most common ones are not so good.} Ba8 $1 {The best move by far, but it was played only in 30 games.} (13... Nf6 {By far the most common, but a bad one.} 14. Qe2 {White just has a better position.} Qc7 (14... c5 {is not possible, because of dxc5 hitting d8.} 15. dxc5 $18) 15. Bf4 {We have already seen this idea.} Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Ne5 {c5 is impossible again.} Nd7 18. c5 $16 {[%csl Rb7] Just look at Black's bishop.}) (13... Qc7 {also bad, the idea is familiar.} 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. c5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb7] bxc5 impossible, and once again, Black has problems with the bishop.}) (13... Bf6 {Third most popular, but just bad.} 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Rac1 {How to continue with Black?} Qc7 16. c5 $16 {[%csl Rb7] Black is always worse, because of the bishop on b7.}) 14. Qe2 c5 {Black really must play this, but it was played only once. It is not an easy move, because after the capture} (14... Qc7 $2 {Once again is a bad move, but almost everybody played like this.} 15. Bf4 $1 {Very bad position for Black.} Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. c5 $16 {[%csl Ra8] Same idea as always.}) (14... Bf6 $6 {is also bad.} 15. Ne5 c5 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 17. Bf4 $16 {Better pieces, just advantage.}) 15. dxc5 {[%cal Gf3e5] Black cannot recapture due to Ne5!, but} Bf6 {is very precise.} 16. Rb1 bxc5 {The best position Black can achieve.} 17. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6]} e5 18. Be3 {We provoked e5, now we can go back and play on the light squares.} Qc7 19. Ne1 $14 {[%csl Ya8,Gd5,Yg2][%cal Gd1d5] White is slightly better without any risk.} *

